1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:09,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:21,000
I'm just going to record a little opening message just for the recording and then we'll start talking.

3
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:26,000
This is David Cline from Virginia Tech and the Southern oral history program.

4
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:35,000
Recording today for the Civil Rights History Project of the Smithsonian's National Museum of African American History and Culture and the Library of Congress.

5
00:00:35,000 --> 00:00:43,000
Today is the 1st of October 2013 and we have the pleasure of being in High Point, North Carolina today with Mr. Robert Brown.

6
00:00:43,000 --> 00:00:54,000
Behind the camera is John Bishop of Media Generation and UCLA and we also have Elaine Nichols from the Museum here today too.

7
00:00:54,000 --> 00:01:00,000
So I just want to start by saying thank you so much for making time in your schedule for us today.

8
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:02,000
Thank you for being here.

9
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:03,000
Yeah, absolutely.

10
00:01:03,000 --> 00:01:06,000
And what I'd like to do, I know we have a lot of ground to cover.

11
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:07,000
Yeah.

12
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:11,000
Fantastic.

13
00:01:11,000 --> 00:01:26,000
So if we could just start with your childhood or even before your childhood, if you like, talking about your family and your roots here, I think in this area, I think that'll be a great place to start.

14
00:01:26,000 --> 00:01:33,000
Okay, I was born and raised here in High Point where I live now.

15
00:01:33,000 --> 00:01:45,000
And my grandmother raised me, was born and raised in Anson County, that's down in Eastern North Carolina.

16
00:01:45,000 --> 00:01:55,000
And her father, his name was Joseph Kimmel's senior, was a slave in that county down there.

17
00:01:55,000 --> 00:02:10,000
And he was one of those who was used to help build the railroads in North Carolina because a lot of the labor building the railroads during that period was slave labor.

18
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:33,000
And interestingly enough, I became a number of years ago, 27 years ago, the Governor appointed me, Governor Jim Martin appointed me to be the president and CEO of the North Carolina Railroad Company, which the state owns the majority shares in now.

19
00:02:33,000 --> 00:02:36,000
And the state owns all the shares in now.

20
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:39,000
It was like coming full circles.

21
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:41,000
Can I say was that four generations?

22
00:02:41,000 --> 00:02:43,000
It's a full circle.

23
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:50,000
And so that's one of the other interesting things, interesting parts of my life that I had to happen.

24
00:02:50,000 --> 00:03:01,000
But early on, my grandmother used to talk about the railroad because she was a maid up at the southern railroad station here in High Point.

25
00:03:02,000 --> 00:03:12,000
And wherever we went, usually if the train went there, we would ride the train because she could get a discount on the tickets.

26
00:03:12,000 --> 00:03:16,000
And so my brother now would go with her all over the place.

27
00:03:16,000 --> 00:03:21,000
And so one day she came to us and said, you know, we're going to catch the bus.

28
00:03:21,000 --> 00:03:25,000
We're going down to her home area called Wadesboro.

29
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:31,000
But we're going to go by way of Fayetteville North Carolina because there's something that I want you all to see.

30
00:03:31,000 --> 00:03:33,000
And we were just small boys.

31
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:36,000
I mean, I was probably eight, nine years old.

32
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:39,000
My brother was 11 or 12.

33
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:44,000
And she said there's something I want you all to see.

34
00:03:44,000 --> 00:03:49,000
And so we got on the bus and went with the Fayetteville North Carolina.

35
00:03:49,000 --> 00:03:51,000
We were going to change buses there.

36
00:03:51,000 --> 00:03:53,000
But there was a layover.

37
00:03:53,000 --> 00:03:58,000
And my grandmother said, we're, come on, we're going to walk on down here.

38
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:10,000
And so she asked, got off the bus and we asked somebody, where is the old slave mart in Fayetteville?

39
00:04:10,000 --> 00:04:13,000
And he fell and says, oh, you go down the street.

40
00:04:13,000 --> 00:04:15,000
She's right down the road there.

41
00:04:15,000 --> 00:04:17,000
So we walked around here.

42
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:26,000
And she said, I just wanted to bring you all here because this was the last place that my father was so.

43
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:30,000
Here in North Carolina was at that slave mart in Fayetteville.

44
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:36,000
And so it's the kind of thing you never really forget.

45
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:48,000
And my grandmother was a saint at Wormen who believed in God and believed in helping everybody and wanted to do something.

46
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:51,000
And she wanted her people to do something.

47
00:04:51,000 --> 00:05:02,000
She wanted me and my brother and her son, my uncle and my mother, daughter, to really do some meaningful things.

48
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:08,000
And what did that do for you or to you seeing that place?

49
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:10,000
I think so.

50
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:18,000
It didn't do as much for me then as it did for me later.

51
00:05:18,000 --> 00:05:22,000
And here I am all these years later.

52
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:24,000
I'm 77 years old.

53
00:05:24,000 --> 00:05:28,000
And I was like eight or nine then.

54
00:05:28,000 --> 00:05:32,000
And I was older up to understand what it was and so forth.

55
00:05:32,000 --> 00:05:34,000
And my brother was two.

56
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:40,000
And the more I grew up and more I studied and I became steep in history.

57
00:05:40,000 --> 00:05:42,000
History was my major subject.

58
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:47,000
It was my major in college in US history in particular.

59
00:05:47,000 --> 00:05:49,000
And I wanted to know more.

60
00:05:49,000 --> 00:05:57,000
I mean, he gave me an insatiable appetite to really get some base knowledge about.

61
00:05:57,000 --> 00:06:03,000
History of America and history of slavery and reconstruction and all that.

62
00:06:03,000 --> 00:06:09,000
So it peaked my interest as a young boy.

63
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:11,000
And I never forgot it.

64
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:13,000
Here I am all these years later.

65
00:06:13,000 --> 00:06:15,000
Generations later.

66
00:06:15,000 --> 00:06:16,000
Decades later.

67
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:18,000
Still talking about that trip.

68
00:06:18,000 --> 00:06:21,000
And it was incredible.

69
00:06:21,000 --> 00:06:24,000
And then we would go down to Wadesboro.

70
00:06:25,000 --> 00:06:29,000
And we go down there, I have private two or three times a year to see her sisters.

71
00:06:29,000 --> 00:06:33,000
They still lived on those farms and so forth.

72
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:36,000
And we would go by on several occasions.

73
00:06:36,000 --> 00:06:43,000
We would go by to see the old house where my grandmother grew up.

74
00:06:43,000 --> 00:06:50,000
It was an old clapboard place with no paint, a big old fireplace in there.

75
00:06:50,000 --> 00:06:54,000
And it was run down and so forth.

76
00:06:54,000 --> 00:07:03,000
And my grandmother would say, you know, we grew up here and we raised cotton and found out he owned a land.

77
00:07:03,000 --> 00:07:06,000
And I would look at this place.

78
00:07:06,000 --> 00:07:10,000
And it was incredible.

79
00:07:10,000 --> 00:07:17,000
And then she say there was an old road, what they call a Rosenwald school.

80
00:07:18,000 --> 00:07:21,000
And there was this old school building right there.

81
00:07:21,000 --> 00:07:26,000
In the school building, I was down there a month and a half ago in that area.

82
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:31,000
And I went by there and this school building is still there and they're trying to renovate it a little bit now.

83
00:07:31,000 --> 00:07:35,000
It's still standing all these years later.

84
00:07:35,000 --> 00:07:41,000
So it really peaked my interest in history and what was going on and all of that.

85
00:07:41,000 --> 00:07:44,000
What was your grandmother's name?

86
00:07:44,000 --> 00:07:50,000
She was a child of the family in the L.I.E., Nelly Marshall Brown.

87
00:07:50,000 --> 00:07:55,000
Her maiden name was Kendall, Nelly Marshall Brown.

88
00:07:55,000 --> 00:07:57,000
Excuse me, second.

89
00:07:57,000 --> 00:08:03,000
Thank you.

90
00:08:03,000 --> 00:08:13,000
All right, so maybe we could talk a little bit about just growing up then here in High Point and what that was like in your school.

91
00:08:13,000 --> 00:08:18,000
It was tough.

92
00:08:18,000 --> 00:08:20,000
You were born in what year now?

93
00:08:20,000 --> 00:08:26,000
I was born in 1935, February 1935.

94
00:08:26,000 --> 00:08:35,000
And we were poor, difficult circumstances.

95
00:08:35,000 --> 00:08:39,000
Everything was segregated.

96
00:08:39,000 --> 00:08:46,000
There's certain water fountains you couldn't drink out of toilets.

97
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:50,000
If you went places, they had a toilet.

98
00:08:50,000 --> 00:08:56,000
If they had a toilet for blacks, most of them did not have a toilet for blacks.

99
00:08:56,000 --> 00:09:00,000
So they had a toilet, but you couldn't use them.

100
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:07,000
Because they had white toilet for men, white toilet for women.

101
00:09:07,000 --> 00:09:11,000
But they had big signs up there, white.

102
00:09:11,000 --> 00:09:14,000
So you knew right away.

103
00:09:14,000 --> 00:09:17,000
But you know, there's a funny thing.

104
00:09:17,000 --> 00:09:26,000
One of my favorite places, the shop, as a young boy and a young kid, was the Woolworth store.

105
00:09:26,000 --> 00:09:38,000
Because they would have a variety of everything, unlike S.H. Kress, S.H. Kress, all of S.H. Kress and some of the others.

106
00:09:38,000 --> 00:09:44,000
Woolworth would always seem to have good, holiday stuff and they'd have a variety of stuff.

107
00:09:44,000 --> 00:09:47,000
So I like to go into the Woolworth store.

108
00:09:47,000 --> 00:09:49,000
And my grandmother would take me to Woolworth store.

109
00:09:49,000 --> 00:09:55,000
So in the back of the Woolworth store, there were the water fountains.

110
00:09:55,000 --> 00:10:00,000
You had white water and you had colored water.

111
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:06,000
Over there, right over the fountain, you had white water and you had colored water.

112
00:10:06,000 --> 00:10:09,000
So I mean, I'm just a little boy.

113
00:10:09,000 --> 00:10:13,000
I don't know that much about the white water, colored water.

114
00:10:13,000 --> 00:10:19,000
And I would be, you know, so one day I'm drinking out of the white water.

115
00:10:19,000 --> 00:10:23,000
Because I just thought maybe the water was just had a little white in it or something.

116
00:10:23,000 --> 00:10:26,000
And so my grandmother saw me.

117
00:10:26,000 --> 00:10:31,000
She was already looking at something and I'm drinking water out of the white water.

118
00:10:31,000 --> 00:10:35,000
And she turned around, saw me drinking out of white water.

119
00:10:35,000 --> 00:10:38,000
And she came over there and she pulled me away from me.

120
00:10:38,000 --> 00:10:40,000
And she said, boy, I don't drink there.

121
00:10:40,000 --> 00:10:45,000
I have white water found in, I said, mama, she said, number water.

122
00:10:45,000 --> 00:10:50,000
It just, it just tastes like the same water is the water over there, the color.

123
00:10:50,000 --> 00:10:53,000
I said, I just want to see what the white water was like.

124
00:10:53,000 --> 00:10:57,000
And she said, that's the same water sign.

125
00:10:57,000 --> 00:11:04,000
It's just that people want you to drink out of the one, the color water.

126
00:11:04,000 --> 00:11:08,000
And she said, one of these days, it'll be changed.

127
00:11:08,000 --> 00:11:13,000
But right now we have to drink out of the white water and the color water.

128
00:11:13,000 --> 00:11:16,000
So I said, well, my mother ate it the same water.

129
00:11:16,000 --> 00:11:20,000
She said, oh, yeah, it's all God's water.

130
00:11:20,000 --> 00:11:22,000
And she said, God's going to change it.

131
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:25,000
He's going to fix it after a while.

132
00:11:25,000 --> 00:11:29,000
She said, I may not have left to see it, but he's going to fix it.

133
00:11:29,000 --> 00:11:33,000
But thank God she lived to see that it was fixed.

134
00:11:33,000 --> 00:11:37,000
And thank God she lived to see that I helped her fix it.

135
00:11:37,000 --> 00:11:48,000
And amazingly, I helped her fix it on many sides.

136
00:11:48,000 --> 00:12:06,000
Because when I went into business in 1961, in early 1961, my first major client was the F.W. Woolworth Co.

137
00:12:07,000 --> 00:12:09,000
My first major client.

138
00:12:09,000 --> 00:12:17,000
And in 1961, there was still color and white water in the South.

139
00:12:17,000 --> 00:12:23,000
In 1961, there was still color and white toilets in 1961.

140
00:12:23,000 --> 00:12:27,000
In 1962, 1963.

141
00:12:27,000 --> 00:12:30,000
And we were became one of my major clients.

142
00:12:30,000 --> 00:12:44,000
And I had, and I think they became a major client because I went to them and told them that they needed to change.

143
00:12:44,000 --> 00:12:59,000
And that there was a change coming and they needed to get with it and have their thing stay in front of it so that they could remain a viable entity in America and eat in the world.

144
00:12:59,000 --> 00:13:02,000
And they wanted to do that.

145
00:13:02,000 --> 00:13:05,000
And they were, I found them interested in doing that.

146
00:13:05,000 --> 00:13:08,000
And it amazed me.

147
00:13:08,000 --> 00:13:26,000
But in a year and a half after I went to them and they hired me to do assessments around the country and to tell them what they ought to be doing in terms of their change in integrating and so forth across the country.

148
00:13:26,000 --> 00:13:35,000
I was the principal advisor on all of this kind of thing, too, that company, it was one of the major companies in America.

149
00:13:35,000 --> 00:13:47,000
And the people on their board of directors from the chairman on down were some of the major financiers in America.

150
00:13:47,000 --> 00:13:56,000
John J. McCloy, who was the High Commissioner in Germany after World War II, the reconstruction.

151
00:13:56,000 --> 00:14:10,000
He was one of the people on their board in the executive committee, Fred Kirby, who was chairman of the Allegheny Corporation, which was the predecessor of all these major hedge funds and all of that.

152
00:14:10,000 --> 00:14:15,000
They owned a New York Central Railroad and a whole lot of other companies.

153
00:14:15,000 --> 00:14:21,000
They were the biggest people financed years in America at that time.

154
00:14:21,000 --> 00:14:29,000
And they were the ones who were responsible for setting policy and everything else at World War.

155
00:14:29,000 --> 00:14:39,000
And so when I got to know them and I got to know what I was doing, they would invite me to their board retreats.

156
00:14:39,000 --> 00:14:48,000
And to go off outings and so forth at the Westchester Country Club.

157
00:14:48,000 --> 00:15:05,000
And I would be making presentations to their board of directors on the kinds of things they ought to be doing and what was happening in America and where we were going and that we needed to be in front of it, not behind it.

158
00:15:05,000 --> 00:15:12,000
And they really believed what I told them. I was fascinated just by that.

159
00:15:12,000 --> 00:15:20,000
And they began to tell me that there were other companies around in America who needed this kind of advice and counsel.

160
00:15:20,000 --> 00:15:26,000
Other companies, many other companies, they controlled all that they were, big shareholders in.

161
00:15:26,000 --> 00:15:34,000
And so they would send me to see other CEOs and chairman of board at this company and that company.

162
00:15:34,000 --> 00:15:43,000
And I got a lot of business, a lot of clients just by following their advice and counsel on who I should go see.

163
00:15:43,000 --> 00:15:57,000
And every time I go tell them that Mr. Kirby sent me all Mr. McCloy, who was the one of the biggest lawyers in America sent me.

164
00:15:57,000 --> 00:16:02,000
So he told me to call you out.

165
00:16:02,000 --> 00:16:05,000
Boom. I had another client immediately.

166
00:16:05,000 --> 00:16:08,000
Well maybe we could back up for just a second and I'll back up a little bit further too.

167
00:16:08,000 --> 00:16:14,000
But if you could tell us just a little bit about the company that you started and when you started it and why?

168
00:16:14,000 --> 00:16:20,000
I started it. I started out as a policeman here in half-point.

169
00:16:20,000 --> 00:16:23,000
Well maybe let's just back up a little bit further and then we'll catch up with that then.

170
00:16:23,000 --> 00:16:28,000
So we were talking about your childhood. Maybe a little bit more about the school that you went to here.

171
00:16:28,000 --> 00:16:34,000
I know that was very important for you and then you're a file.

172
00:16:34,000 --> 00:16:40,000
So we'll take little breaks. We're back.

173
00:16:40,000 --> 00:16:47,000
Well starting out, I started out as a little grade school, not too following my house called Leonard Street School.

174
00:16:47,000 --> 00:17:01,000
I went to the sixth grade there and in the seventh grade all the classes for the black schools went to William Penn High School.

175
00:17:01,000 --> 00:17:12,000
And so I went to William Penn High School which was a school that was founded by the Quakers who dominated the area in North Carolina.

176
00:17:13,000 --> 00:17:21,000
And so I went there in the seventh grade and from then on and I graduated from there in the 12th.

177
00:17:21,000 --> 00:17:34,000
But it was an extraordinary experience there because one of my first major experiences at William Penn was the principal came to me one day and he said,

178
00:17:34,000 --> 00:17:43,000
you know, you're a bright young fella and it's something that I have for you to do and I ask him, yes sir, what is it?

179
00:17:43,000 --> 00:17:50,000
He said, we have Mary McLeod Bethune coming to the school in the next few days.

180
00:17:50,000 --> 00:18:03,000
And I want you to be on your best behavior because I want you to meet her at the door and stay with her and got her around the school all around the school and stay with her until she gets ready to leave.

181
00:18:03,000 --> 00:18:15,000
And that afternoon and that's what I did. I met her at the door and Car came up with. I met her at the door told her who I was and that I was going to be her escort and I escort her around.

182
00:18:15,000 --> 00:18:25,000
And she counseled me all that time for several hours. She would tell me. She asked me about my family about what I wanted to do with my life.

183
00:18:25,000 --> 00:18:35,000
And then she said, you know, you're a bright young man. You're going to do some wonderful things at your life.

184
00:18:35,000 --> 00:18:46,000
But she said, you've got to work hard. She said, you can't. You can't just come in here every day and run and play in everything. You just got to work at it.

185
00:18:46,000 --> 00:18:57,000
And all the way through all day long, she would counsel me and tell me about her life. It was an extraordinary experience.

186
00:18:57,000 --> 00:19:06,000
And that was one of my first real experiences in school that we had.

187
00:19:06,000 --> 00:19:21,000
And then later on, we had people like Langston Hughes to come to the school, people like Dr. Delay Bogeau, who was a professor at Morehouse College, who had graduated for William Penn.

188
00:19:21,000 --> 00:19:37,000
We had Colonel Smith, who became a Colonel in the Army, who had graduated for William Penn to come back and speak and so forth.

189
00:19:37,000 --> 00:19:50,000
So we had a lot of interface with a great number of people who had graduated for William Penn and who had done extremely well to come back.

190
00:19:50,000 --> 00:19:58,000
They would always come back and speak to the kids and do different things with us.

191
00:19:58,000 --> 00:20:09,000
That's one of the things. It was a great experience. And I think that's so deceitful for me wanting to do things.

192
00:20:09,000 --> 00:20:23,000
I was a voracious reader. I stayed in the library. The kids used to pick me up a lot of times. They said, oh man, you're going back to the library again.

193
00:20:23,000 --> 00:20:35,000
I played football and stuff like that, just like other kids. But I was always reading something. I was always reading all the magazines and newspapers.

194
00:20:35,000 --> 00:20:40,000
I want to know what was happening in the country and in the world.

195
00:20:40,000 --> 00:20:53,000
So when I would go to the civics class or something like that, I would know a lot of things. By the time I was in the 10th and the 11th grade, I knew a lot.

196
00:20:53,000 --> 00:21:06,000
I mean, I was up to date on all the current affairs of what was happening in the world. So I became, near the end of the 10th grade, I became the editor of our school paper.

197
00:21:06,000 --> 00:21:21,000
And I think somewhere along the line, I have some of those papers now. And I go back and I read some of the editorials that I wrote as a 11th grade and 12th grade student.

198
00:21:21,000 --> 00:21:35,000
Sometimes I don't believe that. I wrote that. It was in the 11th and 12th grade. But it was extraordinary. And I enjoyed it immensely.

199
00:21:35,000 --> 00:21:50,000
Do you remember some of the things that you read back then? I think it's so interesting to think of being in a relatively small place like High Point, North Carolina. But you were really connecting out to a much larger world. And through some of these people that came to town.

200
00:21:50,000 --> 00:22:08,000
I was reading all the time. First of all, I would read all the magazines, all the big magazines that would come in to the school in the school library. We didn't have money to get a lot.

201
00:22:08,000 --> 00:22:24,000
So whatever came in the magazines in these papers. And then from time to time, we'd have the Sunday New York Times in there from time to time. And then we would have many of the local papers in there.

202
00:22:24,000 --> 00:22:42,000
And I would go in because we didn't have money to get those papers and magazines where. So I'd go in there and I'd read everything in there. And then I'd read different books about what was happening in the world and different things.

203
00:22:42,000 --> 00:23:10,000
So it was, but even more than that, there was a lady who lived across the street from us and they was Mrs. Loudon. And she worked for a wealthy white family. And one day I was sitting on the steps. And I had some old newspapers. I had maybe five or six newspapers that I was going through.

204
00:23:10,000 --> 00:23:25,000
And I'd gotten from somewhere, probably got a mother garbage key because we didn't have money to get books. So newspapers and magazines. So I'd get them, I'd scrounge them up and I'd bring them home and I'd sit down and approach them and steps and read them.

205
00:23:25,000 --> 00:23:43,000
So one day I'm reading these newspapers and so forth. And Mrs. Loudon comes home from work. And she sees me out there reading these newspapers and she stops and she says, Bobby, she said, I see you reading a lot. You love to read, don't you? I said, yes, ma'am.

206
00:23:43,000 --> 00:23:59,000
She said, well, I throw away newspapers and magazines every month up there where I work. And sometimes two or three times a month. She said, they don't keep them. She said, if you'd like them, I'll bring them all home to you.

207
00:23:59,000 --> 00:24:16,000
I said, oh, his members like his like to Lord himself was speaking to me. So for the next few years, she would about two or three times a month. She would bring a big box of newspapers and magazines.

208
00:24:16,000 --> 00:24:33,000
And I mean, it'd be sometimes New York Times and magazines from New York and different kinds of magazines. And I would go through and I would read every one of them.

209
00:24:33,000 --> 00:25:01,000
And so I became, I mean, I could go through a box of stuff and magazines and newspapers. And I found myself all these years later, I still read every day. I read several newspapers. I probably, in the course of any day, I'm at the end of the day. I probably have read

210
00:25:01,000 --> 00:25:30,000
18 sometimes to a 15 newspapers from different parts of the country. I subscribe to newspapers from different parts of the country so that I will know what's happening in different places. And I will have some idea so that when I speak to different groups or I'm giving some thoughts, my thoughts on what's happening in different areas to my clients.

211
00:25:30,000 --> 00:25:53,000
And then, you know, I'm giving it from a factual point of view. I'm not just pulling something out of the wind. And usually when I'm in a meeting, there's the board meeting, major cooperation that I might be in the board, or I might be giving a presentation. And they ask me questions.

212
00:25:53,000 --> 00:26:11,000
And then, times out of ten, I'm going to know what I'm talking about. It's not going to be some theory that something I just looked up in the air and pulled down. You know, I'm going to know what is going on. And that's the way I've been since I was in high school.

213
00:26:11,000 --> 00:26:22,000
And I was that way, I've been that way in business. I've been that way in different things, jobs that I've held. When I was at the White House.

214
00:26:22,000 --> 00:26:41,000
When I would go out of meeting and do it. I had done not only reading, but I had different people who always sent me different kinds of information on different communities and places in the world of information.

215
00:26:41,000 --> 00:26:56,000
And I still have those kind of contexts in Africa and Europe and different places around the world. So when I'm in a board meeting, I've served on a board of directors, some of the largest companies in the world.

216
00:26:56,000 --> 00:27:12,000
And I still serve on a few. And when something comes up about one thing or another, I usually know something about it. I mean, I know the end depth phase of what had happened.

217
00:27:12,000 --> 00:27:30,000
But I usually know something about it. And I can tell you sometimes why it happened here because it happened over there. And it made a trail over here. And it's happening here because somebody wanted that deal over here that happened.

218
00:27:30,000 --> 00:27:44,000
So you know, you can put the dots together. But the only way you can do that is they have the knowledge base to do that. You can't do that on air. And I found that out a long time ago, you know, back in Haskell and Colin.

219
00:27:44,000 --> 00:27:56,000
It's interesting that you see that because I was struck by that just reading about you in your career that you end up operating in this national, obviously, in international circles, but so rooted in the local.

220
00:27:56,000 --> 00:28:09,000
And then coming back home to high point and staying in high point. So it's interesting for me to hear you say how important it is for you to understand what's happening at a very local level in the places where you were.

221
00:28:09,000 --> 00:28:28,000
Yeah, because you know, when I go into a boardroom, when I go to make a presentation to a major group in New York, a London, a Paris or on, like those night years, you know, I know what I'm talking about.

222
00:28:28,000 --> 00:28:47,000
And not only about red, but I've done a lot of background work. And so in after a while in having done it for decades, I can, I can watch the trends in the trends.

223
00:28:47,000 --> 00:29:04,000
And what's the time do not lie, which you got to be able to understand what happened 25 or 30 years ago and how that's coming back into the groove at this point and have some idea of what's going to happen as a direct result of that.

224
00:29:04,000 --> 00:29:30,000
I was telling somebody the other day that many things are happening to American companies now having to do with race related kind of problems because a lot of the management in American companies and other companies have no frame of reference to these kinds of problems.

225
00:29:30,000 --> 00:29:48,000
And what existed because the people who were there earlier who went through this phase went through all the problems. They went through it. So they have an idea, but most of those people either dead or gone, are they retired and they're no longer seen.

226
00:29:48,000 --> 00:29:58,000
The people who are there running many as a company is in many aspects of the country, many divisions of the companies. They have no idea.

227
00:29:58,000 --> 00:30:12,000
They don't have no idea of what happened way back. Oh, maybe they read a memo, but they have no idea about what's happening. And that's why you have today.

228
00:30:12,000 --> 00:30:27,000
And you were going to have even more so, I'd say over the next two or three years, a lot of race related kind of problems, major companies, because they are not prepared to deal with them.

229
00:30:27,000 --> 00:30:39,000
They think because they have somebody who's head of diversity, something like that in the company, which is fun, that that's going to be okay.

230
00:30:39,000 --> 00:30:48,000
But usually the person who's in charge of diversity, they may be black, all that may be white, or maybe he's spani.

231
00:30:49,000 --> 00:31:05,000
But if they're not steeped in the historical aspects of what is going on and how it was fixed before and what you need to do to fix it now and how it kind of changes have been made and what's happening in the marketplace and all that.

232
00:31:05,000 --> 00:31:11,000
If you're not versed in that, you're going to have a problem. The company is going to have a problem.

233
00:31:11,000 --> 00:31:32,000
Or whatever you're allied with, government agencies are going to have a problem. And so now you have problems cropping up all over place as a direct result of people not understanding the dynamics of what any kind of historical reference to what is going on.

234
00:31:32,000 --> 00:31:40,000
Because many of these problems had gone on, they were going on 30, 40 years ago. I've been in this business over 50 years.

235
00:31:40,000 --> 00:31:45,000
And we were dealing with some of this stuff 40 years ago, 30 years ago.

236
00:31:45,000 --> 00:31:46,000
And now you see it coming around again.

237
00:31:46,000 --> 00:31:53,000
You see it coming making full circle, full circle, same kind of stuff.

238
00:31:53,000 --> 00:32:03,000
And because they have no reference, they don't know how to deal with it. And they have no frame of reference on much of this stuff.

239
00:32:03,000 --> 00:32:23,000
So, let's talk, if you could tell us a little bit about your time in Richmond and then coming back here and police officer, federal agent and starting the company.

240
00:32:23,000 --> 00:32:30,000
And then maybe a little bit. What's that? And the name of the company, yeah, of course.

241
00:32:30,000 --> 00:32:34,000
So we'll start with just after high school, I guess.

242
00:32:34,000 --> 00:32:51,000
Well, after high school, I went to Virginia University, I stayed a year there. And then my grandparents who raised me got ill. I came back home and enrolled at North Carolina A&T State University.

243
00:32:51,000 --> 00:33:14,000
I spent a year there and close to the end of that school year, I went to take a police examination because I thought it was directly related to a class in sociology that I was taking on the Dr. Robinson who was the Dean of the School of Social Work.

244
00:33:14,000 --> 00:33:24,000
And it was, I made an A in the course, I took the police exam and helped me generate some thoughts on what ought to be done.

245
00:33:24,000 --> 00:33:43,000
And about two weeks after I took that exam, which was about the end of the school year, I had a meeting, the captain of police detectives came to my house.

246
00:33:43,000 --> 00:33:51,000
And he saw my grandmother and I had come home from school, school was about out and I hadn't come to my own school that afternoon.

247
00:33:51,000 --> 00:34:08,000
So when I got home from Greensboro, my grandmother said to me, Captain Johnson, sort of police station, been here looking for you. And I asked him, was there anything wrong? And he said, no, no, we just want to talk to him.

248
00:34:08,000 --> 00:34:19,000
So my grandmother was, I mean, she was shaking, she was throwing in, but he was not coming back in, you know, policeman, at least captain of conduct detectives, going to your house, me.

249
00:34:19,000 --> 00:34:28,000
Not a good thing. So she said, well, he said he wanted to call him, so was he getting him.

250
00:34:28,000 --> 00:34:39,000
So I went out and called him and I had to go across the street because we didn't have a telephone. And I went across street and this Dunlapse house and called him.

251
00:34:39,000 --> 00:34:48,000
And he said, Robert, you're home, I said, you're certain. He said, well, we're going to come down and see. He said, we just want to chat with you a few minutes.

252
00:34:48,000 --> 00:35:01,000
I said, you're certain. I'll be here. He said, well, we're going to get in the car and come on down there. So police station wasn't that far away. It's downtown, which was about maybe 10 minutes, 15 minutes away.

253
00:35:01,000 --> 00:35:16,000
So he came down and I decided I stand out to him and to push so that my grandmother, my grandfather in the house, so I went on and so I stood out there and they drove up here in another least detective.

254
00:35:16,000 --> 00:35:28,000
Got out the car, came up on the porch and he introduced himself. He said, I'm Captain Johnson from the police department. And he said, we just want to talk to you for a few minutes.

255
00:35:28,000 --> 00:35:38,000
That's a yes sir. What can I do for you? He said, well, we want to offer you a job as a policeman.

256
00:35:38,000 --> 00:35:51,000
I said, off me job. I said, you're kidding. He said, no sir, we're not kidding. He said, you took the police examination and a couple weeks ago.

257
00:35:51,000 --> 00:36:02,000
And you made the highest mark in about an hour and a half. You know, the police examination. And we wanted to reach out to you and see if you want a job.

258
00:36:02,000 --> 00:36:16,000
I had just turned 21 years old. And I said, well, let me think about it. I'll let you know and they'll tell you. He said, okay, well, he's my card and my phone number's on that you call me.

259
00:36:16,000 --> 00:36:28,000
And so I went back in the house and my grandmother, where she was so nervous, my grandfather said, they said, what are you not in any trouble? I said, no man.

260
00:36:28,000 --> 00:36:41,000
So I said, they wanted to offer me a job as a policeman. And I ran them on the sand. Oh, you can't take a job as a policeman. You're in college. You got to go and finish college.

261
00:36:41,000 --> 00:36:51,000
And both of them were ill and money was almost nonexistent. And I said, mama, I said, I don't know. Let me think about it.

262
00:36:51,000 --> 00:37:03,000
And so school was about out. So I went to school and mixed my money. And I thought about it all of that day. And I came back home that afternoon.

263
00:37:03,000 --> 00:37:16,000
And I went in and talked to my grandmother and grandfather. I told them, I said, I think I'll take this job for a year or two. And then I'll go back to school and maybe I can go to school at night, take some night classes.

264
00:37:16,000 --> 00:37:25,000
And so they were along with me and said, you know, I took the job. I stayed on the job for a couple of years.

265
00:37:25,000 --> 00:37:28,000
Were there many black police officers in high point then?

266
00:37:28,000 --> 00:37:42,000
I think there were maybe four or five. There were two black detectives and I think two or three officers.

267
00:37:43,000 --> 00:37:47,000
And but I took the job.

268
00:37:47,000 --> 00:37:51,000
Have were things in the police department then in terms of race relations.

269
00:37:51,000 --> 00:37:57,000
They were they were fair. They weren't the best, but they were fair.

270
00:37:57,000 --> 00:38:06,000
You know, blacks were supposed to be controlling black areas and all that. And were supposed to rest any white people.

271
00:38:06,000 --> 00:38:18,000
I mean, you know, this was written down there. And of course, you know, I got right in the mix because I hadn't been there for about six months.

272
00:38:18,000 --> 00:38:28,000
And one day, my partner, that was a black guy. We got a call. It was a call on the radio. I mean, radio was out there about all the cars.

273
00:38:28,000 --> 00:38:43,000
All cars is a white male loose down off all those street. And he's he's running. And we all cars converge on that area.

274
00:38:43,000 --> 00:38:57,000
And we can need to get him in tow and so forth. Anyway, I went. We went down there. And I grew up in that area. That was the area grew up inside new all the branches and where you could hide and couldn't have.

275
00:38:57,000 --> 00:39:06,000
So I told my partner he drove around. I told him where to let me off. He let me out. And I told him to drive around and wait at the other end of the branch.

276
00:39:06,000 --> 00:39:18,000
Oh, I said on the place that he can run and not expected to be caught is in that branch because everywhere else everybody does see him. And sure enough, that's what this guy did.

277
00:39:18,000 --> 00:39:28,000
He jumped in that branch. It was running out the brain. And so soon as I got out of the car, my guy drove off. I said, just just like running up through that branch.

278
00:39:28,000 --> 00:39:42,000
I mean, he was trucking up to the brain. So I jumped down in that branch. And I said, hey, stop. I said, you under arrest. And he said,

279
00:39:42,000 --> 00:39:53,000
you know, nigga boy, get out of my way. You better get out of my way. You talk about you can't arrest me. No way. I said, I can't. So I took my black jacket out and I hit him with it. Damn.

280
00:39:53,000 --> 00:40:04,000
You know, I drug him out of there. I said, come on, get up. I drug him out of the branch because you know, I had to figure anything could have done that branch. And they wouldn't be finding me on him till he's way away.

281
00:40:04,000 --> 00:40:12,000
So I hit him a couple of times and drug him out of the branch. You've been not hitting me no more with that black jacket. And I hit him again.

282
00:40:12,000 --> 00:40:22,000
So I said, you better get up and walk. I'm going to do more than hit him. I'm going to take my pistol. So he got up. We got him on part of branch.

283
00:40:22,000 --> 00:40:37,000
And soon as we got up out of branch, they were police cars. I hadn't showed up on the other end. So they came back. All the cars converted. My partner and the white guys would have.

284
00:40:37,000 --> 00:40:52,000
And they took him. They came and they took him and they they beat him up. And they threw him in the car. And so I had to go up there and sign a warrant against him in the police station.

285
00:40:52,000 --> 00:41:13,000
And I thought maybe they were something that might say something. Well, you know, you don't have to do that. No. I went up there and signed a warrant. And everything else. And they kept him in jail and just when they had tried to go down the door, threw the book at him. He stayed in jail for a third or four years.

286
00:41:13,000 --> 00:41:34,000
But up until that time, I don't think there had been any kind of in a facing like that. But nobody said anything. So after that was over, you know, nobody. And this was in in 1956 or like that.

287
00:41:34,000 --> 00:41:51,000
And after that was over, nobody thought anything else about it. Nobody ever said you couldn't arrest a white, you know, never written thing. But it just sort of, you know, under current, you know, arrest white people. But then you saw that change.

288
00:41:51,000 --> 00:42:08,000
I saw that change because I arrested several more white people. I know there was a white guy on the Washington Street in a black area. And I was down there one day just walking the street. And he was down there drunk and raised in particular hell on the street.

289
00:42:08,000 --> 00:42:22,000
And so I saw all of the blacks looking at the Bobby shop doors and everything, you know, and they were wondering what I was going to do because I'm there, you know, I'm just patrolling on foot that day.

290
00:42:22,000 --> 00:42:31,000
And so I'm walking down the street and this guy's kind of losing about half-duced and he's walking out street cursing and raising and saying it.

291
00:42:31,000 --> 00:42:43,000
And then he saw me, he looked up me, saw me, and he called me a nigga, you know, and stuff. So I said, okay. So I crossed the street over where he was and I said, you're on the rest.

292
00:42:43,000 --> 00:42:57,000
And he says, oh, he called me a nigga again. You can't arrest me. You better get out of my way. So I took my black jacket out and hit him one time. It's hard as I could hit him.

293
00:42:57,000 --> 00:43:06,000
And he said, oh, you better hit him. And he fell down on one knee. So I took my cups out and put the cups on him and he strapped him up.

294
00:43:06,000 --> 00:43:16,000
And then I told one of the guys in the Bobby shop somebody that you get on your phone and call station telling me to send the card down here. I got somebody on the rest.

295
00:43:16,000 --> 00:43:37,000
And before I could get him up, Adam Cards for sirens or coming, Cards, whatever they came down here. And they threw him in the car and he told me, he said, you better come on up here and sign a warrant and get this rascal, you know.

296
00:43:37,000 --> 00:43:46,000
And I think they probably beat him up a little bit on the way up to you know. So you know, was that kind of a situation.

297
00:43:46,000 --> 00:43:56,000
So it was an interesting, that was an interesting part of my life. And then I got a job as a federal agent as a result of my being a policeman.

298
00:43:56,000 --> 00:44:08,000
I had helped some federal agents do some work. And so I got a job in New York and my post-duty was New York City. I started working on the mafia.

299
00:44:08,000 --> 00:44:22,000
And ended up, you know, a testifying in the Vito Genovese case, which is the biggest mafia case ever. Several of those guys in that case were defended somehow.

300
00:44:22,000 --> 00:44:35,000
And I worked in Canada, the guy who was the biggest mafia guy there, who worked up there. And I worked in Pennsylvania and in New York all over New York.

301
00:44:35,000 --> 00:44:44,000
I made a lot of cases, similar to biggest cases of it in the Bureau. And then after about three years, I decided I didn't want to do that anymore.

302
00:44:44,000 --> 00:44:54,000
I wanted to go into the public relations business. I read about public relations and there's something I wanted to do. And so I read more books and so forth.

303
00:44:54,000 --> 00:45:02,000
So one day I came home and told my wife, I want to go into the public relations business. And she said, oh, Robert, you don't know anything about public relations.

304
00:45:02,000 --> 00:45:12,000
And she said, oh, you know about what you read in those books. You've been reading. I said, yeah, but I know enough to know that this is what I want to do in my life.

305
00:45:12,000 --> 00:45:26,000
Four or five months later, I resigned my job and we packed up and came back to Naka, and my district supervisor at the time in New York had said, you've been a great agent.

306
00:45:26,000 --> 00:45:33,000
And she said, why you want to mess this up? You say you stay here for 20 years and you can retire and you build a young man.

307
00:45:33,000 --> 00:45:44,000
He said, if you go to Naka, I hope my public relations business. You know, you can't get no class. He said, your people can't even go in restaurant.

308
00:45:44,000 --> 00:45:50,000
I said, oh, you talking about you know, my public relations business in North Carolina. See if you go do that, you'll stand in the York.

309
00:45:50,000 --> 00:46:00,000
I said, no, I'm going back to North Carolina to help deal with the problems here. And I said, I'll be able to work everywhere from there.

310
00:46:00,000 --> 00:46:05,000
He said, okay. So I came back. That's his history.

311
00:46:05,000 --> 00:46:13,000
Now, did you have a sense that of the timing at that time that there was something brewing that I knew that there was something brewing?

312
00:46:13,000 --> 00:46:21,000
And the sit-ins had occurred. And then there were things, and I was still reading. And that's what kept me abreast.

313
00:46:21,000 --> 00:46:27,000
You know, New York tribes and all these papers I had to read. I was living in New York, so you know, communication there was great.

314
00:46:27,000 --> 00:46:37,000
And I saw where all these things were happening, all of the country. And I said, oh, something's, this is not going to go away.

315
00:46:37,000 --> 00:46:46,000
It's going to be a change for everyone. And so I decided that that was where I wanted to be. I wanted to be in the arena.

316
00:46:46,000 --> 00:46:55,000
And so I came back home to do that. I didn't feel like I could do that. So the way I wanted to do it in New York, I was like that.

317
00:46:55,000 --> 00:47:02,000
I needed to be in North Carolina. I needed to be where the action was going to be in the South.

318
00:47:03,000 --> 00:47:11,000
Okay. Okay. And so if you could tell us about just the name of the company and when you started it.

319
00:47:11,000 --> 00:47:21,000
Okay. I started at the end of 1960, December 1960. I came back here and started this business.

320
00:47:22,000 --> 00:47:31,000
And then, you know, I pursued it and I had a 1960 Ram, a car.

321
00:47:31,000 --> 00:47:41,000
And I would go around. I made up a list of the companies. I made up a scenario of what I wanted to do and so forth.

322
00:47:41,000 --> 00:47:50,000
And I wanted to do it. And then I went around to see if I could go in these doors, go in the doors and see these people at these companies.

323
00:47:50,000 --> 00:47:56,000
And I got to see a lot of them. I drive different places. And many times I'd have to sleep in my car.

324
00:47:56,000 --> 00:48:02,000
Well, I was if he was in the South, I'd sleep in my car because I couldn't get a hotel.

325
00:48:02,000 --> 00:48:10,000
And if I was in the North, many times, if I was driving in New York or somewhere else, many times I wouldn't have the money.

326
00:48:10,000 --> 00:48:19,000
I'd have to have the money to save money for my gas. And so I'd sleep in my car, go to the wire and have a shower and shade and change clothes.

327
00:48:19,000 --> 00:48:29,000
And I'd keep a nice, press suit and shirt and tie it. And they wouldn't know whether I came out of the walled off a story, but I came out of back in my car.

328
00:48:29,000 --> 00:48:39,000
So I would do that. And that's the way I pursued it. And I pursued it with some big up and kept doing it.

329
00:48:39,000 --> 00:48:41,000
And the company name?

330
00:48:41,000 --> 00:48:47,000
The name of my company is B and C Associates. When I started out, I had a friend of mine.

331
00:48:47,000 --> 00:48:59,000
He had just come back from the service. He'd been in service. And he stayed with me. His name was Campbell.

332
00:48:59,000 --> 00:49:08,000
And he stayed with me for about three months. And after that time, he says, hey, look, I gotta go find myself a job. My wife says, I have to find a job.

333
00:49:08,000 --> 00:49:17,000
And I said, I don't know what this thing is going to work here. So he left. And I just never changed the name. I said, hey, look, what's in the name anyway.

334
00:49:17,000 --> 00:49:23,000
So I kept the name and kept on moving.

335
00:49:24,000 --> 00:49:42,000
So often, I think when we think of the movement or making change, we think of these big public events and not what's happening behind the scenes or the closed doors or the money or the public relations that it takes.

336
00:49:42,000 --> 00:49:48,000
Could you talk a little bit about what it does take to make change happen, to make a movement?

337
00:49:49,000 --> 00:49:50,000
From a company point of view?

338
00:49:50,000 --> 00:49:52,000
Yeah, from a company point of view.

339
00:49:52,000 --> 00:49:59,000
Yeah, I mean, both, I think. And I'll ask some more questions too, but we'll start there.

340
00:49:59,000 --> 00:50:14,000
You could say from a civil rights point of view. I had access to a number of companies. I had some access to some funding from these companies.

341
00:50:15,000 --> 00:50:43,000
And I did some very innovative things because what I would do is, for instance, when I started working closer with Dr. (Martin Luther) King and Reverend White, T. Walker, who was Dr. (Martin Luther) King's assistant and executive vice president of the SCLC, he was literally running everything on a day-to-day basis.

342
00:50:44,000 --> 00:50:56,000
And they needed all kind of help. They told me up front that he'd help and he did. He'd help with money, and he'd logistic who helped with this and that and the other open doors.

343
00:50:56,000 --> 00:51:07,000
And I used what I had. For instance, many of these companies that I worked with, they would budget so much money for this and he said,

344
00:51:07,000 --> 00:51:17,000
that, tell me, you have access to this and any other. And some of them, I didn't have any budget. I mean, I just did what I needed to do and build them for it.

345
00:51:17,000 --> 00:51:36,000
So what I would do is, if Dr. (Martin Luther) King in the moment needed my help in many ways, and many times that was like finding a meeting and the hotels many times would not go along with him for all kinds of reasons.

346
00:51:37,000 --> 00:51:45,000
They'd have them putting up this and then help. And I'd come in and say, okay, I'll pay this bill. I'll pay that bill.

347
00:51:45,000 --> 00:52:02,000
So many of the movements that took place, I underwrote them. And then I would either suck up that bill myself if I had to flexibility that mind of doing that period.

348
00:52:02,000 --> 00:52:17,000
All I would charge off to one of the major companies, Woolworth or something. And then I would tell them, you know, I have to have this flexibility to do, you know, to work with everybody.

349
00:52:17,000 --> 00:52:31,000
And I would just like to build it. You'll work with me. This is where I work. So I just charge it off as a business development kind of thing. And that was it.

350
00:52:31,000 --> 00:52:44,000
Now, what would a Woolworths, you talked about how really one of your first or your first major client really opened the doors to out of other clients. But what did they want from you?

351
00:52:44,000 --> 00:52:53,000
I mean, how did they put that into what did they want you to do for them? I mean, they saw the winds of change, right? But what did that mean exactly?

352
00:52:53,000 --> 00:53:05,000
Well, they didn't know what it means. And seriously, you know, they didn't even understand because nothing like this had ever happened in America before.

353
00:53:05,000 --> 00:53:17,000
Nothing like this had ever happened in our country before. It was nothing that they could compare it with. They couldn't go to the Harvard Business School and say, look, how do you put this?

354
00:53:17,000 --> 00:53:36,000
What is the equation? I was kind of crazy to use on this one. They couldn't do that. And so, you know, I was planning on new ground. There was nothing to compare it. There were no books written on this because none like this had ever happened in America before.

355
00:53:36,000 --> 00:53:49,000
So, I had to use my own judgment, my own ingenuity and so forth. And my ingenuity told me in what my grandmother raised. She said, just do the right thing.

356
00:53:49,000 --> 00:54:03,000
And my grandmother was living in it. I would talk to her many times, tell her, say, mom, I got to deal with this and this and that. And she would tell me. She said, you tell me over and over again.

357
00:54:03,000 --> 00:54:18,000
She said, mom, those are King Jim is a wonderful man. And those fellows, Bob, they're wonderful people. You need to continue to help them. All you can. She said, just do the right thing. And that's what I was trying to do, the right thing.

358
00:54:18,000 --> 00:54:31,000
And I knew they were on solid ground. I knew that that was a winning cause. They had a lot of detractors, many in the black community. And a lot of men in white community, we did not like them.

359
00:54:31,000 --> 00:54:44,000
And so forth. But they were my friends. And I had to figure out all over again, time and time again, how I could be helpful to them, how I could open doors.

360
00:54:44,000 --> 00:54:55,000
And how I could change the attitudes of major business people in the business community about what was happening and how this would be good for our country.

361
00:54:55,000 --> 00:55:20,000
And I've made speeches to different groups, different heads of companies who would be meeting at the Westchester Country Club or other places around the country, different countries companies on race relations on what do you do in a crisis situation and how you should handle it.

362
00:55:20,000 --> 00:55:36,000
And how to deal with change and all that. I mean, these were all new things in America that had never happened in America before. Never.

363
00:55:36,000 --> 00:55:53,000
I mean, you know, since slavery, slavery was one thing. But then the 60s comes in between the 60s and between the 1960s and the 1860s.

364
00:55:53,000 --> 00:56:16,000
You know, you had reconstruction and you had this and another and part of slavery. But there was nothing, nothing that they could compare themselves with that would prepare them for this, but what was happening at that time. So all this was new ground.

365
00:56:16,000 --> 00:56:20,000
Now, did you have to sell them on the power of the black consumer dollar?

366
00:56:20,000 --> 00:56:28,000
Oh, yeah. That was a constant sale. In many times, that would be the only argument that I would have.

367
00:56:28,000 --> 00:56:39,000
Because I would do research and then I hired some professors at A&T. There was a man, his name was Dr. Sidney Evans, who was an economist at A&T.

368
00:56:39,000 --> 00:57:02,000
He became one of my principal consultants. He was consulting with me for 25 years. And he knew a lot about there were other men like Sidney, who I hired to work with me, who wrote papers and did all kinds of things to say to the business community.

369
00:57:02,000 --> 00:57:21,000
And he was here. He is what the black market is. He is what you dealing with. And here is the power in it, not just from the standpoint of economic power, but power of the black church, power of the black schools.

370
00:57:21,000 --> 00:57:31,000
All kinds of latent power within the black community that was going to come and rise up and you had to deal with this.

371
00:57:31,000 --> 00:57:42,000
And that was what I was selling. I was selling that, hey, look, this is coming. Whether you like it or dislike it makes no difference.

372
00:57:42,000 --> 00:57:50,000
So the good of your company and for the good of America, you have to be in front of this. You have to deal with this. You have to make a way.

373
00:57:50,000 --> 00:58:09,000
Because C companies like Woolworth, they didn't even have a black secretary in the Woolworth headquarters building. But they had stores all over the black community in Chicago, New York. They had Woodward stores everywhere in California and Watson.

374
00:58:09,000 --> 00:58:26,000
They had black assistant managers many times in black areas for very few if you know almost no black managers of the stores in black communities.

375
00:58:27,000 --> 00:58:41,000
So I told me we got a dispense, but this we got to go far in a some black men's. We got to train them. We got to bring them in. We got to put people on the board of directors of the company, black people.

376
00:58:41,000 --> 00:58:51,000
You got to put people in the executive office of the company. You got to have black buyers and all that. We did all of that into the work company.

377
00:58:51,000 --> 00:58:59,000
And because we did it there and they were the biggest, the others kind of took on. They didn't have too much of a choice.

378
00:58:59,000 --> 00:59:05,000
Because many of these guys who were on the board, they were the most pop of business men in America.

379
00:59:05,000 --> 00:59:12,000
So if they you know how to business here, you see one doing it and the others almost going to fall in place.

380
00:59:12,000 --> 00:59:21,000
And they saw what was happening to a lot of them who didn't fall in place. You know they were boycotts, they were demonstrations, they were all kinds of things.

381
00:59:21,000 --> 00:59:36,000
Because we work was hitting very hard. And you know the strange thing about go will work thing is that we started working with them in 1961 probably about July, August, 1960.

382
00:59:36,000 --> 00:59:46,000
Four or five years after we started working with them and they were supposed to be in terms of the black community in terms of companies.

383
00:59:46,000 --> 01:00:05,000
The devil re incarnated. And but about five years later, we'll work out two or three awards for being one of the leading companies in terms of civil rights, in terms of integration and all that.

384
01:00:05,000 --> 01:00:10,000
Because we integrated the executive office, we integrated the board.

385
01:00:10,000 --> 01:00:17,000
But you know, we integrated the you look at war stores around the country, we integrated that.

386
01:00:17,000 --> 01:00:26,000
We even had there was a huge war store in in Holland that was owned by blacks.

387
01:00:26,000 --> 01:00:33,000
We had we changed ownership. They had the store when it was burned out for the rights and stuff.

388
01:00:33,000 --> 01:00:41,000
We had a store turned around and we put it in the limited cooperation where it is stored and built in.

389
01:00:41,000 --> 01:00:46,000
Well owned by black is a sale lease bag deal where we worked a long term lease.

390
01:00:46,000 --> 01:00:55,000
And the land and everything was owned by black people. We did that in some communities all across the country.

391
01:00:55,000 --> 01:01:06,000
And now you know, it seems like we've gone backwards because you doing very little of that. Now, we're black people.

392
01:01:06,000 --> 01:01:13,000
You know, other people are still doing all that sale lease bag deals and stuff. But you don't have a lot of black people involved.

393
01:01:13,000 --> 01:01:16,000
We started this all way back.

394
01:01:16,000 --> 01:01:21,000
So Woolworth's new, or I guess I should put this in the form of a question.

395
01:01:21,000 --> 01:01:31,000
So did Woolworth's know that they had, they really had a problem on their hands just the fact that their name became sort of synonymous with picket, with the pickets.

396
01:01:31,000 --> 01:01:32,000
Oh yeah.

397
01:01:32,000 --> 01:01:34,000
And that they had to turn that around in some way.

398
01:01:34,000 --> 01:01:37,000
I think they understood. They understood.

399
01:01:37,000 --> 01:01:44,000
Well, there were some people who didn't want to deal with it, I think.

400
01:01:44,000 --> 01:01:46,000
But they understood.

401
01:01:46,000 --> 01:01:53,000
What kind of resistance did you meet when you took on these projects for the big corporations?

402
01:01:53,000 --> 01:01:57,000
I met with resistance, all kinds of resistance.

403
01:01:57,000 --> 01:02:01,000
I met with resistance in the black community.

404
01:02:01,000 --> 01:02:07,000
I met resistance in the white community.

405
01:02:07,000 --> 01:02:20,000
For instance, in Birmingham, many of the guys who in Dr. (Martin Luther) King was trying to get the stories down there to integrate and so forth.

406
01:02:20,000 --> 01:02:26,000
Well, I was working through Woolworth and some other companies because Woolworth's biggest.

407
01:02:26,000 --> 01:02:30,000
Woolworth says, yeah, they'll do it.

408
01:02:30,000 --> 01:02:39,000
But the rest of them, they're not only going to integrate their lunche account, they didn't want to integrate their lunche rooms and that kind of stuff.

409
01:02:39,000 --> 01:02:43,000
The big department store, they didn't want to hire no blacks and just that number.

410
01:02:43,000 --> 01:02:51,000
So Woolworth was the big daddy in the National Retail Association at the time.

411
01:02:51,000 --> 01:02:56,000
And that was the big daddy of all of them, all the members of that.

412
01:02:56,000 --> 01:03:04,000
So Woolworth had me to meet with those people and get into the facts of life and everything.

413
01:03:04,000 --> 01:03:20,000
And so when Dr. (Martin Luther) King and Dr. Walker went to them and talked to them about, then Woolworth passed a word down that they were going to integrate.

414
01:03:20,000 --> 01:03:33,000
They were going to, not only integrate, they're going to take the business, they're going to figure out a way how to take the business, all the business and have people coming to their stores and so forth.

415
01:03:33,000 --> 01:03:41,000
And so if dollars has done computing, the gas and all the set, everybody starts coming together.

416
01:03:41,000 --> 01:03:54,000
So they got the message, the dollars went up there somewhere, they got the message and they all agreed that there would be a certain time when all of them would come together, all the stores would integrate.

417
01:03:54,000 --> 01:03:57,000
Same way with the hotels.

418
01:03:57,000 --> 01:04:07,000
I remember when Dr. (Martin Luther) King and those integrated the hotels in Memphis, Tennessee, for instance.

419
01:04:07,000 --> 01:04:13,000
In Memphis, there was a hotel called the The Peabody Hotel. That was the main hotel there.

420
01:04:13,000 --> 01:04:16,000
They still be there. It was an old nice hotel.

421
01:04:16,000 --> 01:04:19,000
It is. When it ducks, walk up, you know that.

422
01:04:19,000 --> 01:04:32,000
So Dr. Walker called me one day. He said, Bob, we got a tentative agreement with the The Peabody Hotel in the downtown hotels that they're going to integrate.

423
01:04:32,000 --> 01:04:38,000
And we're going to have a big meeting there at some point in the next couple months.

424
01:04:38,000 --> 01:04:43,000
But we got a test to hotel to see if they're going to do the right thing first.

425
01:04:43,000 --> 01:04:51,000
And he said, Dr. (Martin Luther) King, once you go there and see if they'll let you in and so forth.

426
01:04:51,000 --> 01:04:58,000
So I said, well, okay, if he really wants to do it. So I flew to Memphis.

427
01:04:58,000 --> 01:05:05,000
And some of the guys met me. Some of the SCLC guys met me and they were seeing what was happening.

428
01:05:05,000 --> 01:05:09,000
So I went there and went to the counter and told them I wanted to sweep.

429
01:05:09,000 --> 01:05:13,000
I wanted to want to kind of be a bit sweeter. So they gave me a bit sweet.

430
01:05:13,000 --> 01:05:16,000
Signed me up. I went up there and took the sweep.

431
01:05:16,000 --> 01:05:20,000
And then I came back and I met with some of the guys.

432
01:05:20,000 --> 01:05:26,000
I said, man, y'all coming up. We're going to have some drinks and dinner up daily.

433
01:05:26,000 --> 01:05:29,000
They don't want to see it in a three. It was a big sweep.

434
01:05:29,000 --> 01:05:32,000
The first time I'm black and ever had a sweep.

435
01:05:32,000 --> 01:05:37,000
But they wanted to test it to see what was going on.

436
01:05:37,000 --> 01:05:45,000
But I mean, I used to do so many different things, all over the place, all over the place.

437
01:05:45,000 --> 01:05:51,000
I know that there were some things going on in Richmond.

438
01:05:51,000 --> 01:05:57,000
And Dr. (Martin Luther) King wanted to make sure that they were worked out okay.

439
01:05:57,000 --> 01:06:06,000
And we got in the middle of that. And what walk was a great tactician.

440
01:06:06,000 --> 01:06:13,000
He was a brilliant guy in the movement.

441
01:06:13,000 --> 01:06:18,000
And I don't think he ever really got the kind of critic that he deserved.

442
01:06:18,000 --> 01:06:23,000
Because he was there in doing those difficult days.

443
01:06:23,000 --> 01:06:33,000
He left later on and went to be an executive in a pubs and come to New York and took a large church there and so forth.

444
01:06:33,000 --> 01:06:42,000
And he still lived in, he has been ill last few years and he lives in Virginia.

445
01:06:42,000 --> 01:06:48,000
But there were just, there was so many things going on.

446
01:06:48,000 --> 01:06:53,000
That we were a part of and participating in it some way.

447
01:06:53,000 --> 01:06:57,000
The Poor People's Campaign.

448
01:06:57,000 --> 01:07:01,000
Dr. (Martin Luther) King was planning on that when he was killed, you know, Poor People's Campaign.

449
01:07:01,000 --> 01:07:04,000
This is 1968.

450
01:07:04,000 --> 01:07:09,000
1968 was an unbelievable perilous year.

451
01:07:09,000 --> 01:07:18,000
Because in 1968, I'm working with Dr. (Martin Luther) King in the movement and so forth with the door of the lot of them.

452
01:07:18,000 --> 01:07:24,000
They were holding meetings with planning for the Poor People's Campaign and all of that.

453
01:07:24,000 --> 01:07:27,000
And then Dr. (Martin Luther) King is killed.

454
01:07:27,000 --> 01:07:32,000
And I go with Mr. King to Memphis to pick up his body.

455
01:07:32,000 --> 01:07:37,000
And then we had Dr. (Martin Luther) King's funeral and the night before the funeral,

456
01:07:37,000 --> 01:07:44,000
I had a big suite at the Hyatt Regency where we met with a lot of people.

457
01:07:44,000 --> 01:07:48,000
People like, I think, Sidney Poitier was there.

458
01:07:48,000 --> 01:07:53,000
Robert Kennedy, Robert F. Kennedy, who had met on cell occasions.

459
01:07:53,000 --> 01:07:56,000
He was there with his wife, Ethel.

460
01:07:56,000 --> 01:08:03,000
And just a whole host of people who came to the funeral, talked about where we were going in the country and all of that.

461
01:08:03,000 --> 01:08:11,000
And then later on, after that, Earl Graves, who worked with me in the Bureau.

462
01:08:11,000 --> 01:08:15,000
And we had been friends for a long time, called me and said, you know,

463
01:08:15,000 --> 01:08:20,000
we wanted to push the Robert Kennedy's campaign on the uptune of level.

464
01:08:20,000 --> 01:08:23,000
And I started working with him on that.

465
01:08:23,000 --> 01:08:30,000
And then a few months later, Bob Kennedy is killed in California.

466
01:08:30,000 --> 01:08:34,000
And it was all this happened in 1968.

467
01:08:34,000 --> 01:08:39,000
And then we still try to plan the Poor People's Campaign.

468
01:08:39,000 --> 01:08:48,000
And then a few weeks later, one of my guys who was working for the Nixon Campaign,

469
01:08:48,000 --> 01:08:54,000
who was working for Ray Bliss, who was the chairman of the Republican National Committee.

470
01:08:54,000 --> 01:09:03,000
Black guy, Clarence Townes, wanted me to work with him, give him advice and counsel on what he ought to be doing and all that kind of stuff.

471
01:09:03,000 --> 01:09:07,000
And I agreed to do that two days a week.

472
01:09:07,000 --> 01:09:12,000
Two days ran into five days, five days in the seven days.

473
01:09:12,000 --> 01:09:16,000
And I was handling a lot of different problems for them.

474
01:09:16,000 --> 01:09:26,000
And then after a few weeks, I was called in by Bob Finch, who was running Nixon's campaign.

475
01:09:26,000 --> 01:09:29,000
He was the took of California Chairman Nixon campaign.

476
01:09:29,000 --> 01:09:34,000
He told me that Richard Nixon wanted me to be on a plane with him,

477
01:09:34,000 --> 01:09:37,000
that he'd been watching what I'd been doing for his campaign.

478
01:09:37,000 --> 01:09:41,000
And he wanted me to travel with him.

479
01:09:41,000 --> 01:09:47,000
So I came back home, got myself together, and went back to the campaign in Ohio,

480
01:09:47,000 --> 01:09:55,000
and we went across the state on the last whistle stop train tool that any president has taken in America.

481
01:09:55,000 --> 01:09:57,000
Nixon took it across Ohio.

482
01:09:57,000 --> 01:10:02,000
And that's where we saw the sand with little girl holding up his head, bring us together.

483
01:10:02,000 --> 01:10:07,000
And that became a campaign theme for us.

484
01:10:07,000 --> 01:10:12,000
And I worked in travel with Nixon until the end of the campaign.

485
01:10:12,000 --> 01:10:19,000
And what did you think of Nixon when you first met him or got involved in the campaign?

486
01:10:19,000 --> 01:10:24,000
I thought he was smart.

487
01:10:24,000 --> 01:10:36,000
And many times intuitive and sensitive to a great degree.

488
01:10:36,000 --> 01:10:42,000
I didn't consider him a lot of people wanted to tag him as a racist.

489
01:10:42,000 --> 01:10:45,000
I think he wasn't a racist.

490
01:10:45,000 --> 01:10:48,000
He was everything but a racist.

491
01:10:48,000 --> 01:10:53,000
And then I got to even know him better after the campaign was over.

492
01:10:53,000 --> 01:10:58,000
And after campaign was over, I told him that they wanted me to go to help put your government together,

493
01:10:58,000 --> 01:11:02,000
and put it down to keep us king.

494
01:11:02,000 --> 01:11:08,000
I told him I was going back to North Carolina, put my business back to get there.

495
01:11:08,000 --> 01:11:13,000
I'll take a little pause.

496
01:11:13,000 --> 01:11:17,000
You've been working through your company for Nixon, right?

497
01:11:17,000 --> 01:11:19,000
So you were getting paid for that?

498
01:11:19,000 --> 01:11:22,000
That wasn't volunteer work.

499
01:11:22,000 --> 01:11:29,000
It wasn't regular paid that I think they paid me something at what much.

500
01:11:29,000 --> 01:11:34,000
Now when you worked with the movement, was that all just on your own time?

501
01:11:34,000 --> 01:11:40,000
I was raising money and giving him money.

502
01:11:40,000 --> 01:11:43,000
I was giving it to everybody.

503
01:11:43,000 --> 01:11:46,000
But there was something that I wanted to do.

504
01:11:46,000 --> 01:11:48,000
I needed to do it.

505
01:11:48,000 --> 01:11:51,000
I was making the contacts.

506
01:11:51,000 --> 01:11:54,000
I had the contacts.

507
01:11:54,000 --> 01:11:57,000
And I thought one dog teal into another.

508
01:11:57,000 --> 01:12:00,000
And then I got to see you.

509
01:12:00,000 --> 01:12:06,000
Now did King first reach out to you or how did you make that connection with King and some of the other movement leaders?

510
01:12:06,000 --> 01:12:17,000
I was having lunch in Atlanta with a friend of mine, Stanley S. "Stan" Scott, who read in Atlanta Daily World, like an inspiration.

511
01:12:17,000 --> 01:12:27,000
And he introduced me to Rebel Rev. Wyatt Tee Walker, who was Dr. (Martin Luther) King's right hand man.

512
01:12:27,000 --> 01:12:35,000
And Rebel Walker says to me, he said, you know, he said, you're in a putter relationship and he said, we need your help.

513
01:12:35,000 --> 01:12:39,000
He said, why don't you come back to office when you finish your lunch?

514
01:12:39,000 --> 01:12:45,000
And me with Dr. (Martin Luther) King, he said, Dr. (Martin Luther) King's in town, he would love to meet you.

515
01:12:45,000 --> 01:12:48,000
And I said, you know, no problem.

516
01:12:48,000 --> 01:12:51,000
I said, I like what he's doing.

517
01:12:51,000 --> 01:12:53,000
That's how it happened.

518
01:12:53,000 --> 01:12:55,000
I went by the office of me, Dr. (Martin Luther) King.

519
01:12:55,000 --> 01:12:58,000
Dr. (Martin Luther) King says, hey, look, we need your help.

520
01:12:58,000 --> 01:13:01,000
You know, we need, we try to raise money.

521
01:13:01,000 --> 01:13:04,000
We need the best man we can get.

522
01:13:04,000 --> 01:13:08,000
We just try to make it through him.

523
01:13:08,000 --> 01:13:10,000
That's how we met.

524
01:13:10,000 --> 01:13:12,000
Interesting.

525
01:13:12,000 --> 01:13:17,000
So jumping back to President Nixon, then you were talking about it.

526
01:13:17,000 --> 01:13:22,000
Once that government started to, they started to form that government

527
01:13:22,000 --> 01:13:24,000
and asked you to be a part of that.

528
01:13:24,000 --> 01:13:25,000
Oh, yeah.

529
01:13:25,000 --> 01:13:33,000
And so I initially, you know, I said, no, I can't do that.

530
01:13:33,000 --> 01:13:37,000
I got to go back and make some money.

531
01:13:37,000 --> 01:13:43,000
And so every day I would get a call from Ron, so he'd go to somebody.

532
01:13:43,000 --> 01:13:49,000
But then Nixon office, asking me about this, and what they ought to do about this, then you know.

533
01:13:49,000 --> 01:13:53,000
So one day I got a call from (H.R. "Bob") Haldeman.

534
01:13:53,000 --> 01:14:02,000
This was about a third or four week in November, 68.

535
01:14:02,000 --> 01:14:07,000
And (H.R. "Bob") Haldeman said, Bob, I'm calling you because your man wants to see you.

536
01:14:07,000 --> 01:14:09,000
And he wants to see you right away.

537
01:14:09,000 --> 01:14:12,000
I said, well, I got to come to New York anyway.

538
01:14:12,000 --> 01:14:15,000
Even New York, it was at the Pierre Hotel.

539
01:14:15,000 --> 01:14:17,000
That's where the transition office was.

540
01:14:17,000 --> 01:14:19,000
I said, I'll come back tomorrow.

541
01:14:19,000 --> 01:14:21,000
And I'll come around and come back.

542
01:14:21,000 --> 01:14:25,000
And so I flew to New York.

543
01:14:25,000 --> 01:14:31,000
And went to the Pierre (Hotel) + (H.R.) Haldeman, met me, and he said,

544
01:14:31,000 --> 01:14:33,000
I'll take you with me.

545
01:14:33,000 --> 01:14:36,000
So he took me up to Nixon's suite.

546
01:14:36,000 --> 01:14:45,000
Herbert Brownell Jr and William P. Rogers, when Brownale had been turned to Joe under Eisenhower,

547
01:14:45,000 --> 01:14:50,000
and Rogers was going to be Secretary of State.

548
01:14:50,000 --> 01:14:56,000
He had Nixon had named McCabney, and didn't even have a real staff.

549
01:14:56,000 --> 01:15:04,000
And so when I walked in, the room, and (H.R. "Bob") Haldeman said, Nixon, he said,

550
01:15:04,000 --> 01:15:06,000
oh, I didn't know you had people in here.

551
01:15:06,000 --> 01:15:13,000
He said, I got Bob Brown with me, and we would just wait outside until you finished.

552
01:15:13,000 --> 01:15:14,000
He said, oh, no, no, no, no.

553
01:15:14,000 --> 01:15:16,000
He said, these guys are leaving.

554
01:15:16,000 --> 01:15:17,000
I got to talk to Bob.

555
01:15:17,000 --> 01:15:18,000
He said, bring Bob on in.

556
01:15:18,000 --> 01:15:21,000
I don't want to introduce him to these guys.

557
01:15:21,000 --> 01:15:23,000
So I came in, and he introduced me.

558
01:15:23,000 --> 01:15:25,000
He said, this is Bob Brown.

559
01:15:25,000 --> 01:15:29,000
I want to cheer all of you in here, because you all want to be seeing a lot of him.

560
01:15:29,000 --> 01:15:33,000
He said, he's going to be one of my principal assistants in the White House.

561
01:15:33,000 --> 01:15:37,000
Now we had him have to come and say say, any amount of conversation.

562
01:15:37,000 --> 01:15:41,000
And that's why he introduced me to Brownell and William P. Rogers.

563
01:15:41,000 --> 01:15:43,000
And so they left.

564
01:15:43,000 --> 01:15:47,000
And then (H.R. "Bob") Haldeman says, do you want me to stay at Sticker Brown here?

565
01:15:47,000 --> 01:15:50,000
And he said, oh, no, I want to meet with Bob.

566
01:15:51,000 --> 01:15:57,000
So the two of us met for a long time, maybe 45 minutes or more.

567
01:15:57,000 --> 01:16:05,000
And a lot of the time he's telling me about different things, about the blacks that he knew.

568
01:16:05,000 --> 01:16:15,000
And he started telling me about this story about E. Frederic Morrow, who was in the White House when he was vice president.

569
01:16:16,000 --> 01:16:19,000
And he said, Bob, I know you probably heard.

570
01:16:19,000 --> 01:16:21,000
You might know E. Frederic Morrow.

571
01:16:21,000 --> 01:16:25,000
He said Fred Mar was a top grade guy. He was brilliant smart.

572
01:16:25,000 --> 01:16:31,000
He said, but they had him sitting as the black sitting beside the door.

573
01:16:31,000 --> 01:16:34,000
He said, they didn't give him any real responsibility.

574
01:16:34,000 --> 01:16:37,000
He said, that was wrong. He was a brilliant man.

575
01:16:37,000 --> 01:16:42,000
He said, he was probably smarter than any of the guys that I had around him.

576
01:16:43,000 --> 01:16:45,000
And he said, just didn't give him a break.

577
01:16:45,000 --> 01:16:47,000
He said, but you don't have to worry about that.

578
01:16:47,000 --> 01:16:49,000
You have total access to me.

579
01:16:49,000 --> 01:16:53,000
And he said, in Washington, access is everything.

580
01:16:53,000 --> 01:16:55,000
It's everything.

581
01:16:55,000 --> 01:16:58,000
And he said, you got my confidence and my access.

582
01:16:58,000 --> 01:16:59,000
He said, that's all you need.

583
01:16:59,000 --> 01:17:01,000
He said, no, no, no, don't want your title.

584
01:17:01,000 --> 01:17:04,000
If you got access, you got it all.

585
01:17:04,000 --> 01:17:08,000
And I found out he was right. And he never changed that.

586
01:17:09,000 --> 01:17:14,000
The whole time, I was at the White House for four years and three months.

587
01:17:14,000 --> 01:17:22,000
And to the whole time, I was at the White House.

588
01:17:22,000 --> 01:17:25,000
There was never a 10.

589
01:17:25,000 --> 01:17:29,000
Never a 10 when anybody overruled me.

590
01:17:29,000 --> 01:17:35,000
I mean, there were times when people tried about anything that I did there.

591
01:17:35,000 --> 01:17:37,000
Including the President.

592
01:17:37,000 --> 01:17:40,000
And there were some very sticky situations.

593
01:17:40,000 --> 01:17:52,000
There was one of them where one of the big associations who had given President a lot of money in his campaign.

594
01:17:52,000 --> 01:18:02,000
They wanted to change some of the stuff that I was doing because I was doing the whole Black Economic Development thing and all this.

595
01:18:02,000 --> 01:18:08,000
I was getting Blacks involved with contracts and grants and stuff that they had never been involved with before.

596
01:18:08,000 --> 01:18:13,000
And that was stuff that they had control over to all these contracts.

597
01:18:13,000 --> 01:18:16,000
And they thought I was trading on their ground.

598
01:18:16,000 --> 01:18:23,000
And they told Haldeman they wanted to see the President talk to him about firing me.

599
01:18:23,000 --> 01:18:29,000
Because Haldeman came and told me, he says, you know, these guys, he said, you're going to trade lightly or whatever.

600
01:18:29,000 --> 01:18:34,000
And I said, I'm just doing work. I think the President wants me to do.

601
01:18:34,000 --> 01:18:38,000
So Haldeman says, I got to go tell the President what they want.

602
01:18:38,000 --> 01:18:40,000
I said, we'll tell it. No problem.

603
01:18:40,000 --> 01:18:45,000
So he went to the President, what they wanted.

604
01:18:45,000 --> 01:18:52,000
And Haldeman called me back. He said, Bob, he said, the President wants you to see them.

605
01:18:52,000 --> 01:18:56,000
He said, but the President said, he's not going to see him back to come and see you.

606
01:18:57,000 --> 01:19:00,000
And these guys would give him a lot of money.

607
01:19:00,000 --> 01:19:02,000
And they came and see me.

608
01:19:02,000 --> 01:19:06,000
And I told him, I said, hey, look, we want to work this out.

609
01:19:06,000 --> 01:19:10,000
But it's not going to be the same thing as it's always been.

610
01:19:10,000 --> 01:19:14,000
I said, we want to prove some of nobody is some women in this deal.

611
01:19:14,000 --> 01:19:15,000
These deals in that.

612
01:19:15,000 --> 01:19:17,000
I said, you all had it all.

613
01:19:17,000 --> 01:19:19,000
But we can't do that.

614
01:19:19,000 --> 01:19:23,000
This is a different kind of America where we will be running here right now.

615
01:19:23,000 --> 01:19:26,000
And the President backed me up.

616
01:19:26,000 --> 01:19:29,000
And those guys became friends.

617
01:19:29,000 --> 01:19:35,000
I mean, you know, because I was going to take more than I took.

618
01:19:35,000 --> 01:19:39,000
Now, did the President give you a brief as to what he exactly he wanted to see?

619
01:19:39,000 --> 01:19:40,000
Oh, yeah.

620
01:19:40,000 --> 01:19:45,000
He talked about, he told me in that meeting, at a initial meeting, in the P.R. Hotel.

621
01:19:45,000 --> 01:19:50,000
He said, look, I've talked about in the campaign, he talked about black capitalism.

622
01:19:50,000 --> 01:19:56,000
He said, you know, I made a speech about black spinning business and doing this and that and the other.

623
01:19:56,000 --> 01:20:02,000
He said, but I don't really, he said, you know more about this kind of thing than I do.

624
01:20:02,000 --> 01:20:11,000
He said, you work with art, my little king, you work with civil rights, you travel all over the country with different black groups.

625
01:20:11,000 --> 01:20:15,000
With the church groups and the school.

626
01:20:15,000 --> 01:20:22,000
He said, you need to, you need to handle this.

627
01:20:22,000 --> 01:20:26,000
He said, I'm looking to you to deal with it.

628
01:20:26,000 --> 01:20:30,000
And he said something else that was very important to me.

629
01:20:30,000 --> 01:20:39,000
He said, whenever we have a cabinet meeting, he said, you will be at all the cabinet meetings.

630
01:20:39,000 --> 01:20:43,000
He said, you'll make every time a cabinet meets you will meet.

631
01:20:43,000 --> 01:20:51,000
He said, he'll probably be five or six senior staff in the cabinet meetings.

632
01:20:51,000 --> 01:21:00,000
Every cabinet meeting was held if I was in town, even if I was out of town and could be back there by the time of the meeting.

633
01:21:00,000 --> 01:21:04,000
I mean, out of cheer with my name.

634
01:21:04,000 --> 01:21:08,000
It was your title was special.

635
01:21:08,000 --> 01:21:11,000
No, no, I have a cheer.

636
01:21:11,000 --> 01:21:14,000
But then you could do some other things.

637
01:21:14,000 --> 01:21:22,000
I brought my cheer home, my cheer is in the office down the road of my name.

638
01:21:22,000 --> 01:21:26,000
Let's take a break.

639
01:21:26,000 --> 01:21:27,000
Okay, start again.

640
01:21:27,000 --> 01:21:33,000
How does your end up going south after here in the first place?

641
01:21:33,000 --> 01:21:36,000
Well,

642
01:21:36,000 --> 01:21:50,000
I went to South Africa, I had gone there on a couple of occasions with Ambassador Doug Holliday.

643
01:21:50,000 --> 01:21:53,000
It was especially Ambassador South African.

644
01:21:53,000 --> 01:22:07,000
I also went there to take about 20 black college presidents of South Africa who wanted to go.

645
01:22:07,000 --> 01:22:17,000
And the South African government gave us visas to get ordained because it was hard to get a visa.

646
01:22:17,000 --> 01:22:21,000
So then there's a king called me one day.

647
01:22:21,000 --> 01:22:25,000
She said, Bob, she was a very close friend.

648
01:22:25,000 --> 01:22:28,000
So she said, Bob, I want to go to South Africa.

649
01:22:28,000 --> 01:22:32,000
And you know all those people over there.

650
01:22:32,000 --> 01:22:34,000
And because we can't get a visa.

651
01:22:34,000 --> 01:22:36,000
She said, my people try to get a visa.

652
01:22:36,000 --> 01:22:46,000
So I'll call Piet Koornhof, who was the ambassador to South Africa to the United States.

653
01:22:46,000 --> 01:22:52,000
And I had met Piet at a prep repress in Washington.

654
01:22:52,000 --> 01:22:58,000
And he considered himself as strong about Christian and so forth.

655
01:22:58,000 --> 01:23:00,000
So I told him I wanted to see him.

656
01:23:00,000 --> 01:23:03,000
He said, okay, you come and have lunch with me, Bob.

657
01:23:03,000 --> 01:23:04,000
I said, okay.

658
01:23:04,000 --> 01:23:06,000
So I went to the embassy at lunch with him.

659
01:23:06,000 --> 01:23:13,000
I said, you know, Coretta Scott King, my little King's widow, said she wants to go to South Africa.

660
01:23:13,000 --> 01:23:16,000
And she wants to take to my staff with her.

661
01:23:16,000 --> 01:23:19,000
But she can't get a visa to get into the country.

662
01:23:19,000 --> 01:23:23,000
And I said, this is not the Christian way.

663
01:23:23,000 --> 01:23:26,000
You know, you need to do something else with this.

664
01:23:26,000 --> 01:23:29,000
I said, I don't know what this is, Piet.

665
01:23:29,000 --> 01:23:32,000
You know, you spoke to me, my Christian brother.

666
01:23:32,000 --> 01:23:35,000
But the country is known as this kind of thing.

667
01:23:35,000 --> 01:23:38,000
He said, Bob, no, no, that's not right.

668
01:23:38,000 --> 01:23:40,000
You know, Coretta Scott King wants to go.

669
01:23:40,000 --> 01:23:43,000
I said, you know, I don't know that her.

670
01:23:43,000 --> 01:23:44,000
We have a visa.

671
01:23:44,000 --> 01:23:46,000
He said, you get me all the information.

672
01:23:46,000 --> 01:23:47,000
And we'll get it worked out.

673
01:23:47,000 --> 01:23:48,000
We'll get it again.

674
01:23:48,000 --> 01:23:50,000
I said, okay.

675
01:23:50,000 --> 01:23:52,000
So I'll call Coretta Scott King.

676
01:23:52,000 --> 01:23:55,000
Coretta Scott King has one of the staff to get all the information.

677
01:23:55,000 --> 01:23:58,000
All the people will go.

678
01:23:58,000 --> 01:24:01,000
Got the information.

679
01:24:01,000 --> 01:24:07,000
And within a few days, we had the visa spread by the one to come.

680
01:24:07,000 --> 01:24:12,000
And the other problem was, there were a number of people

681
01:24:12,000 --> 01:24:14,000
who Miss King wanted to go.

682
01:24:14,000 --> 01:24:15,000
They didn't have no money.

683
01:24:15,000 --> 01:24:20,000
I mean, you know, we were doing it under the banner of the King Center,

684
01:24:20,000 --> 01:24:22,000
which she had established.

685
01:24:22,000 --> 01:24:24,000
They didn't have any money.

686
01:24:24,000 --> 01:24:30,000
So I had gotten raised in money for the make the trip.

687
01:24:30,000 --> 01:24:34,000
And so anyway, we went over there.

688
01:24:34,000 --> 01:24:40,000
And one other thing that she said she wanted to do

689
01:24:40,000 --> 01:24:48,000
was to go see (P.W.) Botha to see if we could get him

690
01:24:48,000 --> 01:24:51,000
to let Nelson Mandela out of jail.

691
01:24:51,000 --> 01:24:54,000
She said, I really think I can do this part.

692
01:24:54,000 --> 01:24:56,000
I said, okay, no problem.

693
01:24:56,000 --> 01:24:58,000
This is what year is this?

694
01:24:58,000 --> 01:24:59,000
Approximately?

695
01:24:59,000 --> 01:25:03,000
This was about 19...

696
01:25:03,000 --> 01:25:06,000
1986 maybe.

697
01:25:06,000 --> 01:25:09,000
Okay.

698
01:25:09,000 --> 01:25:13,000
So we went to South Africa.

699
01:25:13,000 --> 01:25:19,000
And when we got there,

700
01:25:19,000 --> 01:25:27,000
we met with a group of people in South Africa,

701
01:25:27,000 --> 01:25:31,000
like Dr. Allan Boesak and others.

702
01:25:31,000 --> 01:25:39,000
And they all were urging us not to meet.

703
01:25:39,000 --> 01:25:44,000
The music king shouldn't meet with (P.W.) Botha.

704
01:25:44,000 --> 01:25:48,000
And he said, okay.

705
01:25:48,000 --> 01:25:53,000
And Miss King, some of the people that she had taken with her,

706
01:25:53,000 --> 01:25:59,000
and I said they were rethinking the meeting with (P.W.) Botha.

707
01:25:59,000 --> 01:26:04,000
And so, after we got there, we stayed up all night discussing

708
01:26:04,000 --> 01:26:08,000
with some of the leadership in South Africa

709
01:26:08,000 --> 01:26:13,000
and some of the people who lead U.S., in the US saying

710
01:26:13,000 --> 01:26:17,000
that most of them came to conclusion that we shouldn't meet

711
01:26:17,000 --> 01:26:19,000
with (P.W.) Botha.

712
01:26:19,000 --> 01:26:22,000
And that's one of the reasons Miss King was over there.

713
01:26:22,000 --> 01:26:24,000
She's over there for a couple of reasons.

714
01:26:24,000 --> 01:26:28,000
One of the other reasons was

715
01:26:28,000 --> 01:26:33,000
to be made an archbishop at the time.

716
01:26:33,000 --> 01:26:39,000
And she was going to attend his ceremony.

717
01:26:39,000 --> 01:26:48,000
And nobody, when it came to meet with (P.W.) Botha,

718
01:26:48,000 --> 01:26:53,000
she wanted to meet with (P.W.) Botha to ask for him

719
01:26:53,000 --> 01:26:58,000
a medal out of jail and a medal out of jail.

720
01:26:58,000 --> 01:27:05,000
And see, this is something that never really is surfaced.

721
01:27:05,000 --> 01:27:10,000
But most of the people in that meeting,

722
01:27:10,000 --> 01:27:15,000
they didn't want Miss King to meet with (P.W.) Botha.

723
01:27:15,000 --> 01:27:19,000
So we thrashed that out over all night long.

724
01:27:19,000 --> 01:27:20,000
I mean, literally all night.

725
01:27:20,000 --> 01:27:22,000
And we're still at talk about this.

726
01:27:22,000 --> 01:27:24,000
So Miss King decided to say, Bob,

727
01:27:24,000 --> 01:27:27,000
I don't want to go against the wishes of the people

728
01:27:27,000 --> 01:27:29,000
here on the ground and dealing with this.

729
01:27:29,000 --> 01:27:31,000
She said, I'm not going to do this.

730
01:27:31,000 --> 01:27:36,000
She said, I'm going to write a letter to (P.W.) Botha

731
01:27:36,000 --> 01:27:41,000
and tell him that I can't meet with him and so forth.

732
01:27:41,000 --> 01:27:43,000
So she wrote the letter.

733
01:27:43,000 --> 01:27:47,000
And of course, who gets picked to take the letter

734
01:27:47,000 --> 01:27:50,000
to the State House.

735
01:27:50,000 --> 01:27:55,000
So I told him I would do it after he picked me.

736
01:27:55,000 --> 01:28:02,000
So I went over there to tell him that she wasn't going to be

737
01:28:02,000 --> 01:28:07,000
meeting with him because he had agreed to meet with her.

738
01:28:07,000 --> 01:28:10,000
And he wouldn't meet with anybody, but he had agreed to meet with her.

739
01:28:10,000 --> 01:28:13,000
And she was going to ask me, the man tell us release,

740
01:28:13,000 --> 01:28:15,000
but she didn't want to.

741
01:28:15,000 --> 01:28:22,000
So anyway, I took the letter and I went through the gate.

742
01:28:22,000 --> 01:28:25,000
I let me through the gate and went to (P.W.) Botha's office.

743
01:28:25,000 --> 01:28:28,000
And this guy met me when his assistance met me.

744
01:28:28,000 --> 01:28:32,000
And I delivered the letter and I said, please give us a letter

745
01:28:32,000 --> 01:28:34,000
from Miss King to (P.W.) Botha.

746
01:28:34,000 --> 01:28:36,000
And I said, she deeply regrets this.

747
01:28:36,000 --> 01:28:39,000
She could not meet with him at this time.

748
01:28:39,000 --> 01:28:42,000
And he looked at me and he said, Mr. Brown,

749
01:28:42,000 --> 01:28:47,000
he said, we certainly appreciate Miss King Bing here.

750
01:28:47,000 --> 01:28:52,000
And we appreciate you delivering this letter to (P.W.) Botha

751
01:28:52,000 --> 01:28:55,000
telling him what Miss King's wishes were.

752
01:28:55,000 --> 01:28:57,000
And he said, we respect her wishes.

753
01:28:57,000 --> 01:29:00,000
And I said, thank you very much.

754
01:29:00,000 --> 01:29:06,000
And we were called to maybe greeting you again sometimes.

755
01:29:06,000 --> 01:29:09,000
So I turned around left.

756
01:29:09,000 --> 01:29:13,000
So I went back and Miss King says, Bob,

757
01:29:13,000 --> 01:29:16,000
she said, one of the things that I need to do before I leave this country,

758
01:29:16,000 --> 01:29:19,000
I need to go see Winnie Mandela.

759
01:29:19,000 --> 01:29:21,000
Now we went Cape Town.

760
01:29:21,000 --> 01:29:26,000
Johannesburg is two and a half hours away by plane.

761
01:29:26,000 --> 01:29:31,000
And so we got in touch with Miss Mandela, Miss Mandela.

762
01:29:31,000 --> 01:29:34,000
So you had to love to see Miss King.

763
01:29:34,000 --> 01:29:36,000
So we flowed to Johannesburg.

764
01:29:36,000 --> 01:29:39,000
Went to Soweto.

765
01:29:39,000 --> 01:29:41,000
It spends some time with Miss Mandela.

766
01:29:41,000 --> 01:29:45,000
So we're sitting there talking, talking, talking about everything.

767
01:29:45,000 --> 01:29:53,000
And so Miss King asked, Miss Mandela, what would you,

768
01:29:53,000 --> 01:29:57,000
what would be most important to you and Miss Mandela for us

769
01:29:57,000 --> 01:30:00,000
that we could do for you all now?

770
01:30:00,000 --> 01:30:04,000
And Miss Mandela was loud and clear.

771
01:30:04,000 --> 01:30:11,000
She said, the thing that Nelson and I want most is for our children

772
01:30:11,000 --> 01:30:15,000
to be able to go back to America and go to school.

773
01:30:15,000 --> 01:30:19,000
She said that there are a number of people over here who promise that.

774
01:30:19,000 --> 01:30:21,000
But nobody has ever delivered.

775
01:30:21,000 --> 01:30:25,000
So you know, people promise in America, and you never hear from them anymore.

776
01:30:25,000 --> 01:30:31,000
That's what Miss Mandela told Miss King.

777
01:30:31,000 --> 01:30:37,000
So Miss King looked at me and she says, Bob, is this something that we can do?

778
01:30:37,000 --> 01:30:40,000
I knew what she meant.

779
01:30:40,000 --> 01:30:42,000
So I told her.

780
01:30:42,000 --> 01:30:46,000
I told her, I told Miss Mandela, I said, I told Miss King, I said, yes, I think we can do it.

781
01:30:46,000 --> 01:30:54,000
And I said, but what we need, what I need is I need a letter from Miss Mandela

782
01:30:54,000 --> 01:30:58,000
to me personally asking me to do this.

783
01:30:59,000 --> 01:31:02,000
And then I'll set it in the motion.

784
01:31:02,000 --> 01:31:12,000
And sure enough, about two or three weeks later, I get a letter from Miss Mandela asking me to do this.

785
01:31:12,000 --> 01:31:18,000
And so I set it in the motion.

786
01:31:18,000 --> 01:31:23,000
I called President Boston University, who's a close friend, and I was on that board.

787
01:31:23,000 --> 01:31:26,000
I'm still on that board of trustees in the university.

788
01:31:26,000 --> 01:31:33,000
And he agreed to do, he agreed to take care of the tuition and so forth.

789
01:31:33,000 --> 01:31:41,000
But I would have to take care of all the other expenses, getting them over here, house, a van

790
01:31:41,000 --> 01:31:45,000
because they had Mandela's three grandchildren at time.

791
01:31:45,000 --> 01:31:49,000
It was four because he had another child and thinks he got it.

792
01:31:49,000 --> 01:31:53,000
And they lived here seven years.

793
01:31:53,000 --> 01:31:54,000
Seven years.

794
01:31:54,000 --> 01:31:57,000
And I paid for it personally.

795
01:31:57,000 --> 01:32:04,000
Not some grant I got from the foundation of from a company, from RGB personally.

796
01:32:04,000 --> 01:32:08,000
And it was a very expensive proposition.

797
01:32:08,000 --> 01:32:15,000
But it was one that I did because I thought we owed it to them.

798
01:32:15,000 --> 01:32:21,000
And I had told Miss King, who was one of my closest friends that I would do it.

799
01:32:21,000 --> 01:32:24,000
And I did it.

800
01:32:24,000 --> 01:32:33,000
Now, that young woman who came over here is now the South African ambassador to Argentina,

801
01:32:33,000 --> 01:32:36,000
Uruguay, and Paraguay.

802
01:32:36,000 --> 01:32:50,000
She's the only person, only Mandela, a child, a grandchild, who is in an official position with the government.

803
01:32:50,000 --> 01:32:53,000
And that's the money.

804
01:32:53,000 --> 01:32:54,000
Incredible.

805
01:32:54,000 --> 01:33:02,000
So, you never know how things are going to turn out when you pursue different kinds of activity.

806
01:33:02,000 --> 01:33:05,000
But South Africa was a real challenge.

807
01:33:05,000 --> 01:33:08,000
And you met him as soon as he got out of prison?

808
01:33:08,000 --> 01:33:11,000
I met him inside the jail.

809
01:33:11,000 --> 01:33:15,000
I have some material that I'll share with you.

810
01:33:15,000 --> 01:33:18,000
But I met him inside the jail.

811
01:33:18,000 --> 01:33:26,000
They allowed Mrs. Mandela to look when I agreed to take him over and bring him back with me.

812
01:33:26,000 --> 01:33:33,000
I went over there and Mrs. Mandela said, before you lead this country again, you have to see Nelson Mandela.

813
01:33:33,000 --> 01:33:36,000
I said, well, nobody has seen him in 27 years.

814
01:33:36,000 --> 01:33:38,000
How do you think they're going to let me see him?

815
01:33:38,000 --> 01:33:42,000
I said, didn't want me to let you all see him, but 15 minutes of the 10,

816
01:33:42,000 --> 01:33:46,000
and you all traveled 2.5 hours down in Cape Verri from Javasper.

817
01:33:46,000 --> 01:33:48,000
She said, well, I'm going to try.

818
01:33:48,000 --> 01:33:55,000
I'm going to petition President Botha for you to see him, because you're taking you to God in him, his children.

819
01:33:55,000 --> 01:34:04,000
And I thought it was hopeless, useless, hopeless kind of thing for her to do, because I knew they wouldn't want to do that.

820
01:34:05,000 --> 01:34:14,000
The night before I was to leave, I got a call from Niel van Heerden, who was one of the top assistants to President Botha.

821
01:34:14,000 --> 01:34:21,000
And he called me on telephone at the hotel. He said, Mr. Brown, because he said what his name was.

822
01:34:21,000 --> 01:34:23,000
He said, I'm calling for President Botha.

823
01:34:23,000 --> 01:34:29,000
He asked me to call you to tell you that you have permission.

824
01:34:30,000 --> 01:34:38,000
He's granting you permission to see Mr. Mandela tomorrow at Pollsmoor Prison, if you still want to do it.

825
01:34:38,000 --> 01:34:40,000
I couldn't believe it.

826
01:34:40,000 --> 01:34:44,000
Nobody had seen Nelson Mandela in 20-something years.

827
01:34:44,000 --> 01:34:49,000
These people grant me permission to go to Pollsmoor Prison to see him inside the prison.

828
01:34:49,000 --> 01:34:52,000
I mean, it was just so.

829
01:34:52,000 --> 01:34:59,000
I figured maybe they want to kill me, because you know there are a lot of killings and bombings and everything going on with me.

830
01:34:59,000 --> 01:35:02,000
And so I said, oh my goodness.

831
01:35:02,000 --> 01:35:04,000
So I prayed over it.

832
01:35:04,000 --> 01:35:10,000
I asked God to give me strength in the guidance and give me the courage to go ahead and do this.

833
01:35:10,000 --> 01:35:15,000
So I went down to him.

834
01:35:15,000 --> 01:35:21,000
I carried Zenani Mandela and Prince Moosey, a husband with me.

835
01:35:21,000 --> 01:35:28,000
And so we got to the gate and you know they had all these guns and things there.

836
01:35:28,000 --> 01:35:33,000
And that's so, oh my God, it's maybe it's maybe it.

837
01:35:33,000 --> 01:35:38,000
So the guy brought out his big old pad and he says, oh you must have brought him.

838
01:35:38,000 --> 01:35:39,000
He said, yeah.

839
01:35:39,000 --> 01:35:48,000
He said, well, we were going to open the gate and you go to that red brick building up there.

840
01:35:48,000 --> 01:35:53,000
And somebody will come and meet you at the door as soon as you get there.

841
01:35:53,000 --> 01:35:58,000
So we walked through the gate, walked up there to this brick building.

842
01:35:58,000 --> 01:36:04,000
And as soon as I got to the bottom of the steps of the big building, only about three or four steps there,

843
01:36:04,000 --> 01:36:13,000
this big white guy comes out and he grabs my hand.

844
01:36:13,000 --> 01:36:18,000
And he said, Mr. Brown, he said, I'm the cheap warden here.

845
01:36:18,000 --> 01:36:25,000
And what you're doing for Mr. Mandela is a marvelous thing for his family.

846
01:36:25,000 --> 01:36:31,000
And we all want to congratulate you and for what you're doing for Mr. Mandela and his family.

847
01:36:31,000 --> 01:36:35,000
He said, I'm having him brought down from his cell now.

848
01:36:35,000 --> 01:36:38,000
And you go into that big room over there in the corner.

849
01:36:38,000 --> 01:36:42,000
And you sit in there and you talk to him as long as you want to.

850
01:36:42,000 --> 01:36:49,000
Now in 20 some years, nobody is family who they want people to go out and see.

851
01:36:49,000 --> 01:36:53,000
They were on this, let him be seen for 15 or 20 minutes.

852
01:36:53,000 --> 01:36:56,000
And then sometimes they give him an extra 15 minutes.

853
01:36:56,000 --> 01:36:59,000
And they were traveling two and a half hours by plane.

854
01:36:59,000 --> 01:37:05,000
And I've sat there and talked to him about two hours.

855
01:37:05,000 --> 01:37:08,000
He was absolutely mind-boggling.

856
01:37:08,000 --> 01:37:12,000
He told me what it would take to make peace inside the bathroom.

857
01:37:12,000 --> 01:37:14,000
He talked about a lot of things.

858
01:37:14,000 --> 01:37:18,000
I have a memo that I wrote as soon as I got out of the house,

859
01:37:18,000 --> 01:37:22,000
scratching their notes and having a memo that I wrote.

860
01:37:22,000 --> 01:37:31,000
As soon as I got out of the gate and I'll give you a copy of it.

861
01:37:31,000 --> 01:37:34,000
A memo that I wrote about how to meet him.

862
01:37:34,000 --> 01:37:37,000
And then they let me go back the next year.

863
01:37:37,000 --> 01:37:40,000
They let me go back to see him again.

864
01:37:40,000 --> 01:37:45,000
But by this time they were talking to him.

865
01:37:45,000 --> 01:37:49,000
They had never really had any relationship or talked to him.

866
01:37:49,000 --> 01:37:51,000
It wouldn't matter if I didn't talk.

867
01:37:51,000 --> 01:37:56,000
But after I saw him and I wrote this memo and I passed it on to Mrs. Mandela.

868
01:37:56,000 --> 01:37:58,000
She gave it to the ANC.

869
01:37:58,000 --> 01:38:01,000
I passed it on to George Shultz, who was Secretary of State.

870
01:38:01,000 --> 01:38:04,000
I passed it on to President Reagan.

871
01:38:04,000 --> 01:38:08,000
I gave a peak corn off and wrote a copy of it.

872
01:38:08,000 --> 01:38:11,000
So they could send it to President Reagan.

873
01:38:11,000 --> 01:38:12,000
And so forth.

874
01:38:12,000 --> 01:38:15,000
So everybody had it outside, and their side had it.

875
01:38:15,000 --> 01:38:22,000
A&C had everybody had the memo about what Mrs. Mandela was talking about.

876
01:38:22,000 --> 01:38:28,000
And so after that they had started the little conversations with him.

877
01:38:28,000 --> 01:38:30,000
And things started to roll.

878
01:38:30,000 --> 01:38:32,000
What they let it to another and another.

879
01:38:32,000 --> 01:38:35,000
So you just never know what God has in store for you.

880
01:38:35,000 --> 01:38:38,000
And how he's using you.

881
01:38:38,000 --> 01:38:42,000
It's my grandmother used to say, just let God have His way.

882
01:38:42,000 --> 01:38:44,000
Let Him use you.

883
01:38:44,000 --> 01:38:48,000
And things will turn out okay.

884
01:38:48,000 --> 01:38:57,000
But it was an unbelievable time down there in South Africa.

885
01:38:57,000 --> 01:38:59,000
It was amazing.

886
01:38:59,000 --> 01:39:03,000
And then there were other things that happened during that period.

887
01:39:03,000 --> 01:39:08,000
I went into most of the black townships, all of the country.

888
01:39:08,000 --> 01:39:14,000
And I would go to the schools because I figured that was the schools.

889
01:39:14,000 --> 01:39:16,000
And see if they were in the library.

890
01:39:16,000 --> 01:39:23,000
Well, there were very few of almost no libraries because they wouldn't let them have books.

891
01:39:23,000 --> 01:39:37,000
So what I did, it's I decided to start taking books, sending books back to South Africa.

892
01:39:37,000 --> 01:39:47,000
And so as a result, I would take truck rolls of the mega commission from the South African government

893
01:39:47,000 --> 01:39:50,000
that I could bring shoes and clothes.

894
01:39:50,000 --> 01:39:53,000
I didn't tell them I'd bring books.

895
01:39:53,000 --> 01:40:01,000
So in every box of shoes and clothes, I'd have a half a box of shoes and clothes and a half a box of books.

896
01:40:01,000 --> 01:40:04,000
All kinds of school books.

897
01:40:04,000 --> 01:40:08,000
And so I started doing that on a scale.

898
01:40:08,000 --> 01:40:12,000
And I would be going there.

899
01:40:12,000 --> 01:40:15,000
I'd make my point to go there, get the books in there.

900
01:40:15,000 --> 01:40:20,000
And then I get a truck from here, a truck loaded up.

901
01:40:20,000 --> 01:40:28,000
And I'd got permission from the South African government to put those books on South African highways.

902
01:40:28,000 --> 01:40:32,000
And they didn't charge me anything for putting them on there.

903
01:40:32,000 --> 01:40:36,000
So I put those books in the clothes because I told them they were shoes and clothes.

904
01:40:36,000 --> 01:40:39,000
And they look in the box, that's what they would see.

905
01:40:39,000 --> 01:40:42,000
Shoes and clothes, but the other half of the box were number of books.

906
01:40:42,000 --> 01:40:45,000
So I did that for several years.

907
01:40:45,000 --> 01:40:49,000
I took books into...

908
01:40:49,000 --> 01:40:51,000
And you still do that, right?

909
01:40:51,000 --> 01:40:52,000
And still do that.

910
01:40:52,000 --> 01:40:59,000
We set up over 300 live areas in South Africa, over 300.

911
01:41:00,000 --> 01:41:08,000
We set them up in the Zulus in (likely) Zululand, with the King of the Zulus,

912
01:41:08,000 --> 01:41:11,000
who is also a good friend.

913
01:41:11,000 --> 01:41:16,000
And before you leave, I'll show you some pictures.

914
01:41:16,000 --> 01:41:19,000
And we set all of South Africa.

915
01:41:19,000 --> 01:41:25,000
Because books are still precious in Africa, not just in South Africa.

916
01:41:25,000 --> 01:41:28,000
And Africa books are like gold.

917
01:41:28,000 --> 01:41:31,000
A kid gets a book and they start to cry.

918
01:41:31,000 --> 01:41:36,000
And we are threading books over here.

919
01:41:36,000 --> 01:41:43,000
We are threading books about millions, you know, recycling them in their country.

920
01:41:43,000 --> 01:41:48,000
When these people, millions, tens of millions of kids don't have any books.

921
01:41:48,000 --> 01:41:52,000
And they think a book, like a piece of gold.

922
01:41:52,000 --> 01:41:55,000
And they try to make it a book.

923
01:41:55,000 --> 01:41:58,000
So we're going to have to figure that out.

924
01:41:58,000 --> 01:42:01,000
How's your book?

925
01:42:01,000 --> 01:42:04,000
It's in the low end.

926
01:42:04,000 --> 01:42:06,000
You ready to start again?

927
01:42:06,000 --> 01:42:09,000
So maybe let's start there, if you would.

928
01:42:09,000 --> 01:42:13,000
Talk a little bit about President Nixon and his character,

929
01:42:13,000 --> 01:42:18,000
and how he felt about working on race relations.

930
01:42:18,000 --> 01:42:23,000
So to really hear about the work that you are able to do

931
01:42:23,000 --> 01:42:28,000
in stimulating the growth of minority businesses.

932
01:42:28,000 --> 01:42:35,000
Well, first of all, I think a lot of people

933
01:42:35,000 --> 01:42:44,000
have put together in their own minds that President Nixon was devout races.

934
01:42:44,000 --> 01:42:47,000
He was a devout quaker.

935
01:42:47,000 --> 01:42:51,000
And I don't know any racist quakers.

936
01:42:51,000 --> 01:42:55,000
I know that sometimes President Nixon used some language

937
01:42:55,000 --> 01:42:59,000
that he probably regretted or shouldn't have used.

938
01:42:59,000 --> 01:43:03,000
But many people do that.

939
01:43:03,000 --> 01:43:08,000
But many people didn't have a camera on them when they were doing it.

940
01:43:08,000 --> 01:43:11,000
Many Presidents have done that.

941
01:43:11,000 --> 01:43:15,000
And many top people have been around a few when they've used

942
01:43:15,000 --> 01:43:17,000
some bad language.

943
01:43:17,000 --> 01:43:20,000
So he's not the only one who's done that.

944
01:43:20,000 --> 01:43:24,000
But he's the only one who had that camera on him who could

945
01:43:24,000 --> 01:43:25,000
you could show.

946
01:43:25,000 --> 01:43:27,000
And so he was condemned for it.

947
01:43:27,000 --> 01:43:32,000
But he was not a racist.

948
01:43:32,000 --> 01:43:35,000
He was a person.

949
01:43:35,000 --> 01:43:39,000
If he believed in you or if he believed in a cause,

950
01:43:39,000 --> 01:43:41,000
he was totally for it.

951
01:43:41,000 --> 01:43:44,000
And the whole thing of minority business enterprise.

952
01:43:44,000 --> 01:43:48,000
He wanted to have blacks and Hispanics and others

953
01:43:48,000 --> 01:43:52,000
to get a shot.

954
01:43:52,000 --> 01:43:57,000
Because he felt very strongly that if you don't get a shot

955
01:43:57,000 --> 01:44:03,000
within the business community or in business in general,

956
01:44:03,000 --> 01:44:06,000
this whole country is built on that.

957
01:44:06,000 --> 01:44:10,000
And if you were not involved in that,

958
01:44:10,000 --> 01:44:14,000
it was going to be very limited in terms of what you were going

959
01:44:14,000 --> 01:44:17,000
to be able to do in America.

960
01:44:17,000 --> 01:44:19,000
And so he wanted that open up.

961
01:44:19,000 --> 01:44:23,000
And my charge was to do that.

962
01:44:23,000 --> 01:44:25,000
I went to Wall Street.

963
01:44:25,000 --> 01:44:28,000
I went to the biggest banks in the country.

964
01:44:28,000 --> 01:44:31,000
The city group was the biggest bank of the time.

965
01:44:31,000 --> 01:44:35,000
Met with their chairman and CEO and vice chairman

966
01:44:35,000 --> 01:44:38,000
about the whole minority enterprise program

967
01:44:38,000 --> 01:44:41,000
of what we expected in them and their bank to do.

968
01:44:41,000 --> 01:44:43,000
They agreed to work with us.

969
01:44:43,000 --> 01:44:47,000
We organized a national commission on minority enterprise.

970
01:44:47,000 --> 01:44:51,000
And we put the most powerful people in America.

971
01:44:51,000 --> 01:44:57,000
And in it, we designated this chairman of that group,

972
01:44:57,000 --> 01:45:00,000
Mr. Roche, who was James M. Roche,

973
01:45:00,000 --> 01:45:03,000
who was the chairman and CEO of GM,

974
01:45:03,000 --> 01:45:06,000
which at the time was the largest corporation in America

975
01:45:06,000 --> 01:45:10,000
and deed in the world at that time.

976
01:45:10,000 --> 01:45:14,000
He agreed to chair it, not only did he agree to chair it,

977
01:45:14,000 --> 01:45:17,000
but he got other industrial people,

978
01:45:17,000 --> 01:45:23,000
other automobile manufacturers to come on in and give dealerships

979
01:45:23,000 --> 01:45:26,000
to blacks all over the country.

980
01:45:26,000 --> 01:45:31,000
When we went to the White House in late 1968,

981
01:45:31,000 --> 01:45:37,000
in the head, there were only, I think there were only two.

982
01:45:37,000 --> 01:45:41,000
No more than three blacks in America who had

983
01:45:41,000 --> 01:45:44,000
who owned dealerships.

984
01:45:44,000 --> 01:45:49,000
And there were very few who were working in many of these major

985
01:45:49,000 --> 01:45:53,000
manufacturers, you know, like Chrysler, GM, Ford.

986
01:45:53,000 --> 01:45:56,000
Very few were working, almost none.

987
01:45:56,000 --> 01:46:00,000
They were working in the executive positions in these companies.

988
01:46:00,000 --> 01:46:03,000
And they were the top of the day.

989
01:46:03,000 --> 01:46:07,000
Now, I mean, it wasn't people seem to think

990
01:46:07,000 --> 01:46:11,000
that, you know, because you have some blacks there now

991
01:46:11,000 --> 01:46:15,000
and some top positions and all that on boards and so forth,

992
01:46:15,000 --> 01:46:18,000
that all this just happened by osmosis.

993
01:46:18,000 --> 01:46:21,000
It did not happen by osmosis.

994
01:46:21,000 --> 01:46:25,000
It happened because we worked at it and made it happen.

995
01:46:25,000 --> 01:46:29,000
You know, I met James M. Roche became a close personal friend of that.

996
01:46:29,000 --> 01:46:33,000
And when we left the White House, he wanted to expand

997
01:46:33,000 --> 01:46:36,000
what they were doing in terms of a Nord enterprise.

998
01:46:36,000 --> 01:46:40,000
And James M. Roche hired my company for several years to go out

999
01:46:40,000 --> 01:46:44,000
and spirit the word and to get them involved in a whole range

1000
01:46:44,000 --> 01:46:49,000
of different kinds of activities with a Nord is across the country.

1001
01:46:49,000 --> 01:46:52,000
So, you know, it just didn't happen.

1002
01:46:52,000 --> 01:46:56,000
You know, just because I was there and I was sitting up there

1003
01:46:56,000 --> 01:46:58,000
as a black person, it doesn't.

1004
01:46:58,000 --> 01:47:01,000
It makes some difference whether you are a black person sitting

1005
01:47:01,000 --> 01:47:05,000
where I was sitting as a staff person or if you are a black person sitting

1006
01:47:05,000 --> 01:47:07,000
as a president in the United States.

1007
01:47:07,000 --> 01:47:10,000
If you want some stuff to happen, you got to work at it.

1008
01:47:10,000 --> 01:47:13,000
You know, you just can't wish it to happen.

1009
01:47:13,000 --> 01:47:15,000
You got to make it happen.

1010
01:47:15,000 --> 01:47:17,000
And that's what we were doing.

1011
01:47:17,000 --> 01:47:18,000
That's what we did.

1012
01:47:18,000 --> 01:47:22,000
And that's what the Nixon years were all about.

1013
01:47:22,000 --> 01:47:26,000
And that's what the President Nixon in 1972,

1014
01:47:26,000 --> 01:47:32,000
when he ran for reelection, he got 20% of more of the black vote.

1015
01:47:32,000 --> 01:47:37,000
And he was supposed to be, according to some history books

1016
01:47:37,000 --> 01:47:42,000
and some people, he was supposed to be the devil reincarnated to blacks.

1017
01:47:42,000 --> 01:47:49,000
No Republican candidate since 1972 has gotten as many black votes

1018
01:47:49,000 --> 01:47:52,000
as Richard Nixon got in 1972.

1019
01:47:52,000 --> 01:47:54,000
No candidate.

1020
01:47:54,000 --> 01:47:56,000
How did that happen?

1021
01:47:56,000 --> 01:47:59,000
When he was supposed to be the devil reincarnated.

1022
01:47:59,000 --> 01:48:05,000
We had Jim Brown, we had Sammy Davis Jr.,

1023
01:48:05,000 --> 01:48:10,000
we had the president of the Baptist conventions

1024
01:48:10,000 --> 01:48:14,000
and some Baptist convention, we had some of the top ministers

1025
01:48:14,000 --> 01:48:18,000
in the country and bishops of different churches and so forth.

1026
01:48:18,000 --> 01:48:23,000
Who came out in support of President Nixon in 1972.

1027
01:48:23,000 --> 01:48:25,000
That's how it happened.

1028
01:48:25,000 --> 01:48:29,000
Because they knew we were working closer with them.

1029
01:48:29,000 --> 01:48:36,000
They knew that we had a major effort to get major money into black colleges.

1030
01:48:36,000 --> 01:48:40,000
We got the first major money into black colleges,

1031
01:48:40,000 --> 01:48:42,000
in ever in America.

1032
01:48:42,000 --> 01:48:44,000
Richard Nixon did that.

1033
01:48:44,000 --> 01:48:47,000
We, as no president before,

1034
01:48:47,000 --> 01:48:57,000
since has met with all of the top black that he had in his top positions in administration.

1035
01:48:57,000 --> 01:49:01,000
We would meet with all of them at least once a year,

1036
01:49:01,000 --> 01:49:04,000
sometimes twice during the course of the year.

1037
01:49:04,000 --> 01:49:08,000
And people who were in that group with people like James Farmer Jr,

1038
01:49:08,000 --> 01:49:11,000
who was assistant secretary of HEW,

1039
01:49:11,000 --> 01:49:14,000
who was the head of CORE.

1040
01:49:14,000 --> 01:49:19,000
At that time, it was considered the most radical organization there was on the scene.

1041
01:49:19,000 --> 01:49:23,000
He was conducted massive demonstrations and everything else.

1042
01:49:23,000 --> 01:49:28,000
But we brought him into the administration as an assistant secretary of HEW

1043
01:49:28,000 --> 01:49:31,000
in a top job where he could make things happen.

1044
01:49:31,000 --> 01:49:33,000
Where he did make things happen.

1045
01:49:33,000 --> 01:49:35,000
We had other people there,

1046
01:49:35,000 --> 01:49:37,000
here to the Wormers Bureau and the Labor Department.

1047
01:49:37,000 --> 01:49:40,000
We had Arthur A. Fletcher there, who was assistant secretary of labor,

1048
01:49:40,000 --> 01:49:43,000
who came up with the Philadelphia plan.

1049
01:49:43,000 --> 01:49:47,000
And all those things derived to ship, which we caught to employment.

1050
01:49:47,000 --> 01:49:50,000
All those things started under Richard Nixon.

1051
01:49:50,000 --> 01:49:52,000
All those things.

1052
01:49:52,000 --> 01:49:54,000
And we had people in those jobs,

1053
01:49:54,000 --> 01:49:58,000
and who came in mass, we had them in mass, in a way out.

1054
01:49:58,000 --> 01:50:04,000
I have pictures here to show you what we were doing and who we were meeting with.

1055
01:50:04,000 --> 01:50:08,000
And these pictures would go out to the Washington Post,

1056
01:50:08,000 --> 01:50:12,000
New York Times and all that about these meetings and all this stuff that was going on.

1057
01:50:12,000 --> 01:50:16,000
And I don't think not one is our call.

1058
01:50:16,000 --> 01:50:23,000
Not one major newspaper printed any of these pictures.

1059
01:50:23,000 --> 01:50:25,000
Not one major newspaper.

1060
01:50:25,000 --> 01:50:29,000
Now, there's something wrong with that.

1061
01:50:29,000 --> 01:50:36,000
Not one major newspaper printed in these pictures of all of this that happened all over the place.

1062
01:50:36,000 --> 01:50:41,000
So there were so many different things going on.

1063
01:50:41,000 --> 01:50:45,000
Job situations, EEOC.

1064
01:50:45,000 --> 01:50:51,000
The first major funding and revamping of EEOC to take it to another level so it could be more effective.

1065
01:50:51,000 --> 01:50:53,000
Was done under Richard Nixon.

1066
01:50:53,000 --> 01:51:02,000
And William H. Brown III, who's a big lawyer, who made a lot of strats in America, was chairman of it.

1067
01:51:02,000 --> 01:51:04,000
For four years.

1068
01:51:04,000 --> 01:51:06,000
He's filled it out for you, lawyer.

1069
01:51:06,000 --> 01:51:08,000
Talked one of the top lawyers in the country.

1070
01:51:08,000 --> 01:51:10,000
Black lawyer.

1071
01:51:10,000 --> 01:51:16,000
And there were other things like that that happened over and over again,

1072
01:51:16,000 --> 01:51:23,000
where we brought top people, civil rights leaders and other wrong Wilkins, Whitney M. Young Jr.

1073
01:51:23,000 --> 01:51:26,000
The president met with Whitney M. Young Jr many times.

1074
01:51:26,000 --> 01:51:30,000
The president met with Roy Wilkins, who was head in double-ACP many times.

1075
01:51:30,000 --> 01:51:35,000
We did all kinds of things as a result of their suggestions.

1076
01:51:35,000 --> 01:51:39,000
What about the federal government patronizing black businesses?

1077
01:51:39,000 --> 01:51:41,000
Was that a priority that they started?

1078
01:51:41,000 --> 01:51:43,000
That was a big problem.

1079
01:51:43,000 --> 01:51:52,000
And that was something that I pursued at a white house level in that Secretary Maurice H. Stans who was Secretary of Commerce.

1080
01:51:52,000 --> 01:51:56,000
He and I worked very closely together with that.

1081
01:51:56,000 --> 01:52:03,000
He had the responsibility because we set up the office of the minority of business enterprise within the Commerce Department.

1082
01:52:03,000 --> 01:52:08,000
And we pursued that with all of the departments of the government.

1083
01:52:08,000 --> 01:52:14,000
And not only did we pursue it in terms of contracts and grants,

1084
01:52:14,000 --> 01:52:20,000
but along with all the other things that I was doing, I made sure that the Defense Department,

1085
01:52:20,000 --> 01:52:28,000
that the other departments that had a lot of money, like General Services Administration, all that,

1086
01:52:28,000 --> 01:52:38,000
I made sure that they were giving out contracts and grants and whatever they had to black contractors,

1087
01:52:38,000 --> 01:52:46,000
to the black colleges and universities, just as they were doing to other people that they hadn't been doing before we got there.

1088
01:52:46,000 --> 01:52:57,000
The figure that I have is that the federal government purchases from black businesses rose from $13 million to $142 million during Nixon's tenure.

1089
01:52:57,000 --> 01:52:59,000
During your tenure?

1090
01:52:59,000 --> 01:53:00,000
Oh yeah.

1091
01:53:00,000 --> 01:53:01,000
I know.

1092
01:53:01,000 --> 01:53:03,000
Because we monitored it.

1093
01:53:03,000 --> 01:53:06,000
It's another thing we monitored.

1094
01:53:06,000 --> 01:53:12,000
In the Korean War, not the Korean War, but Vietnam War was going on at the time.

1095
01:53:12,000 --> 01:53:18,000
We were having big trouble, the race-relation problem, and a big race-relation problem.

1096
01:53:18,000 --> 01:53:22,000
When we got to the White House, that was one of the big problems.

1097
01:53:22,000 --> 01:53:29,000
And blacks were not being promoted.

1098
01:53:29,000 --> 01:53:32,000
They were at a certain level.

1099
01:53:32,000 --> 01:53:48,000
So when we got to White House in 1969, when Nixon was inaugurated, we had, I think, two or more than three blacks who were Abel, General, and most of the departments,

1100
01:53:48,000 --> 01:53:50,000
all that was in the army, I believe.

1101
01:53:50,000 --> 01:53:59,000
I think we had one Navy guy, (uncertain - Navy admiral) Samuel L. Gravely Jr, I think he was a real Abel.

1102
01:53:59,000 --> 01:54:00,000
But that was it.

1103
01:54:00,000 --> 01:54:08,000
When we got there in 1969, one of the things that happened, you know, and I started concentrating on this.

1104
01:54:08,000 --> 01:54:19,000
And Daniel "Chappie" James Jr, who we brought over to be the Deputy Assistant Secretary of Defense for Public Affairs, and gave him a star, because he was a Colonel.

1105
01:54:19,000 --> 01:54:25,000
He was an ace pilot in two wars, one of the top guys in military that we've ever had.

1106
01:54:26,000 --> 01:54:31,000
And he was a Colonel, and it was ace pilot in two wars.

1107
01:54:31,000 --> 01:54:34,000
And we brought him over, gave him a star, and put him into the first part.

1108
01:54:34,000 --> 01:54:49,000
But when Chappy came to me one day and he said, Bob, he said, we're never going to have a representative number of blacks, unless we get something going on here in this defense department.

1109
01:54:49,000 --> 01:54:50,000
It's never going to happen.

1110
01:54:51,000 --> 01:54:53,000
So I said, we're going to do something about it, Chappie."

1111
01:54:53,000 --> 01:54:56,000
So I talked to a hallemar about it.

1112
01:54:56,000 --> 01:55:03,000
And he said, let me go talk to President, and let me tell him, and he said, I'm going to wait until President ever talking to him, see what he said.

1113
01:55:03,000 --> 01:55:05,000
And I'll call you back.

1114
01:55:05,000 --> 01:55:09,000
About two or three hours later, I could just call from Hallemann.

1115
01:55:09,000 --> 01:55:17,000
Hallemann said, Bob, I talked to President, and President thinks he were exactly right, and he wants to be helpful.

1116
01:55:17,000 --> 01:55:32,000
He said, he figured out the way that he could be helpful is that every month they send over the list of flag offices, because there's a command and chief, he has to sign off on it.

1117
01:55:32,000 --> 01:55:43,000
And so in order to do something about that, Bob, he said, what I'm going to do in the President agreed, what I'm going to do is send you the list.

1118
01:55:43,000 --> 01:55:55,000
And when it comes over, you check it out and see if any minorities on the list, he said, if there are no minorities, he said, you let me know, and we'll send it right on back.

1119
01:55:55,000 --> 01:56:01,000
We send it back about three or four times in a row.

1120
01:56:01,000 --> 01:56:14,000
And so all of a sudden, it must have done on somebody, depending on that, we better do something else.

1121
01:56:14,000 --> 01:56:23,000
So they start putting some blacks on there, put a woman on there, and so I would check it out.

1122
01:56:23,000 --> 01:56:40,000
And so we started when they started doing that, by the time I left the White House in 1973, we had a whole lot of black generals.

1123
01:56:40,000 --> 01:56:48,000
Okay, a whole lot of them, and then they come all over the place after that.

1124
01:56:48,000 --> 01:56:56,000
By the time I left there, a chapter of James, who had never had a star when we got there, we gave him his first star.

1125
01:56:56,000 --> 01:57:00,000
By the time I left, he had three stars.

1126
01:57:00,000 --> 01:57:14,000
And he was the head of our military base in Dingo, that strategic base that we have out there.

1127
01:57:14,000 --> 01:57:20,000
But there were just so many things like that that happened over and over.

1128
01:57:20,000 --> 01:57:32,000
I mean, it was vastly important. It changed the way we did business in America, with the military, with business people, with all facets of what we were trying to do.

1129
01:57:32,000 --> 01:57:38,000
But we had to weigh it in on it. I even set up a special commission.

1130
01:57:38,000 --> 01:57:42,000
I did this myself, because I had the President, it's okay to do whatever.

1131
01:57:42,000 --> 01:57:51,000
I set up a special commission to go around the world, because we were having race-relations problems, on military bases, all over the world.

1132
01:57:51,000 --> 01:57:59,000
I set up a special commission to go around the world, to check this out, and meet with the service people in all these bases.

1133
01:57:59,000 --> 01:58:02,000
You find all kinds of problems.

1134
01:58:02,000 --> 01:58:10,000
And then I would go from time to time, I would go myself, unannounced, until I got right there near the base.

1135
01:58:10,000 --> 01:58:18,000
And I'd have somebody at one of the military guys on the plane with me to call the base and tell him that I'm going to be landing this plane.

1136
01:58:18,000 --> 01:58:24,000
He's going to be landing this plane in the next 30 minutes, and that I'm going to meet with the command in office.

1137
01:58:24,000 --> 01:58:30,000
Because we'd have intelligence that would be telling us what was happening on different places.

1138
01:58:30,000 --> 01:58:36,000
I went to Hawaii. There were a lot of tear in the white, because we had a lot of military bases there.

1139
01:58:36,000 --> 01:58:49,000
And the person who was the head of CINCPAC, all of the armed forces in the Far East and from the White White back, was none other than Admiral John S. McCain Jr.

1140
01:58:49,000 --> 01:58:51,000
John McCain's father.

1141
01:58:51,000 --> 01:58:57,000
I have a picture with him right here somewhere, but he and I are meeting over there in Hawaii.

1142
01:58:57,000 --> 01:59:02,000
We became good friends as a result of that.

1143
01:59:02,000 --> 01:59:05,000
So it was quite a time.

1144
01:59:05,000 --> 01:59:07,000
Amazing work that you did there.

1145
01:59:07,000 --> 01:59:10,000
So I have just...

1146
01:59:10,000 --> 01:59:13,000
Okay.

1147
01:59:13,000 --> 01:59:18,000
Yeah, so just conclude if you could tell us about Sealtest in AMP.

1148
01:59:18,000 --> 01:59:29,000
Well, I got this call one day from one of the guys who was traveling to Dr. (Martin Luther) King.

1149
01:59:29,000 --> 01:59:32,000
And Dr. (Martin Luther) King was in Cleveland.

1150
01:59:32,000 --> 01:59:39,000
And he said that Dr. (Martin Luther) King would talk to me, and he wanted me with me.

1151
01:59:39,000 --> 01:59:44,000
And I had a man coming out here and I said, oh no, I can't snake the plane out there.

1152
01:59:44,000 --> 01:59:47,000
So when I airport, John don't play with Cleveland.

1153
01:59:47,000 --> 01:59:54,000
And when I got there, Dr. (Martin Luther) King came in room, he said, Bob, he said, we got a problem here.

1154
01:59:54,000 --> 01:59:59,000
And he said, we got a problem with Sealtest.

1155
01:59:59,000 --> 02:00:12,000
He said, you know, we've been trying to meet with them and get them to hire black truck drivers and do some other kinds of things that they need to be doing.

1156
02:00:12,000 --> 02:00:15,000
And he said, they won't even meet with me.

1157
02:00:15,000 --> 02:00:19,000
They refused to meet with me or any of my people.

1158
02:00:19,000 --> 02:00:26,000
And he said, I'm wondering if you have any suggestions of what we can do.

1159
02:00:26,000 --> 02:00:32,000
And I told him, I said, yeah, I said, what I need to do.

1160
02:00:32,000 --> 02:00:40,000
I said, I have this relationship with the people at A&P, with the top people at AMP,

1161
02:00:40,000 --> 02:00:44,000
and the time it's a larger supermarket chain in America.

1162
02:00:44,000 --> 02:00:49,000
And I said, you know, I will go to them, I'll call them up, see if I can see them.

1163
02:00:49,000 --> 02:00:53,000
And I'll fly there immediately and see what I can do about it.

1164
02:00:53,000 --> 02:00:59,000
And he said, well, we need to do something because we want to make some progress, but we're going to have to,

1165
02:00:59,000 --> 02:01:03,000
we don't want to tear up everything and make any progress.

1166
02:01:03,000 --> 02:01:14,000
So I flew to New York and got a meeting with the CEO of A&P.

1167
02:01:14,000 --> 02:01:19,000
And when I went in the room, we expressed the greetings and so forth.

1168
02:01:19,000 --> 02:01:22,000
And I told them, let me get right to the point.

1169
02:01:22,000 --> 02:01:24,000
He was the point.

1170
02:01:24,000 --> 02:01:29,000
I said, Dr. (Martin Luther) King and his people are in the Cleveland Ohio area.

1171
02:01:29,000 --> 02:01:34,000
And they're going to have a lot of problems with Sealtest dairy.

1172
02:01:34,000 --> 02:01:39,000
I said, the Sealtest management won't meet with Dr. (Martin Luther) King or any of his people.

1173
02:01:39,000 --> 02:01:42,000
And I said, there's going to be big trouble there.

1174
02:01:42,000 --> 02:01:47,000
And I said, we do not need the A&P stores because AMP was a cloud of that.

1175
02:01:47,000 --> 02:01:50,000
So I said, we don't need the A&P stores involved in this.

1176
02:01:50,000 --> 02:01:58,000
We're trying to make room in all of the states where A&P is located to have a new relationship.

1177
02:01:58,000 --> 02:02:01,000
And I said, we need to be in front of this.

1178
02:02:01,000 --> 02:02:04,000
And he said, well, Bob, what would you recommend?

1179
02:02:04,000 --> 02:02:10,000
I said, I would recommend that you have somebody to get in touch with A&P,

1180
02:02:10,000 --> 02:02:13,000
one of our top executives.

1181
02:02:13,000 --> 02:02:20,000
And let them know with Sealtest and let them know that we have a problem with this.

1182
02:02:20,000 --> 02:02:24,000
And we don't want to be involved some kind of way.

1183
02:02:25,000 --> 02:02:29,000
And he said, you're right, Bob.

1184
02:02:29,000 --> 02:02:31,000
Then he called in one of his top assistants.

1185
02:02:31,000 --> 02:02:36,000
He came in the room and he said, look, Bob's been telling me about his problem with Sealtest.

1186
02:02:36,000 --> 02:02:38,000
And he said, yes, sir.

1187
02:02:38,000 --> 02:02:39,000
We know all about it.

1188
02:02:39,000 --> 02:02:42,000
It's a problem not to end the Midwest.

1189
02:02:42,000 --> 02:02:49,000
And he said, well, I want you to call the top people with Sealtest and tell them

1190
02:02:50,000 --> 02:02:55,000
that if they don't get this situation right with Dr. (Martin Luther) King,

1191
02:02:55,000 --> 02:03:04,000
that we are going to take Sealtest products out of all of the stores in Ohio.

1192
02:03:04,000 --> 02:03:11,000
Now, I had recommended initially that maybe we ought to look at taking the products out of all the stores in Cleveland.

1193
02:03:11,000 --> 02:03:16,000
He told him to tell me the products out of all the stores in Ohio.

1194
02:03:17,000 --> 02:03:23,000
Before I could hardly get out of the building because I had some more meetings there.

1195
02:03:23,000 --> 02:03:31,000
Before I could get out of the building, I called my office and my office told me that

1196
02:03:31,000 --> 02:03:36,000
Dr. (Martin Luther) King, people are desperately trying to reach you.

1197
02:03:36,000 --> 02:03:39,000
They still include, they need you to talk to you.

1198
02:03:39,000 --> 02:03:43,000
So I called out to King.

1199
02:03:43,000 --> 02:03:48,000
Dr. (Martin Luther) King said, Bob, he said, I don't know what you told them people.

1200
02:03:48,000 --> 02:03:53,000
He said, but the top people at Sealtest have called me several times already.

1201
02:03:53,000 --> 02:03:56,000
They want to meet this afternoon.

1202
02:03:56,000 --> 02:03:57,000
They want to meet in the morning.

1203
02:03:57,000 --> 02:04:04,000
And every time we can meet, they want to meet there at the meet and work with us anyway they can.

1204
02:04:04,000 --> 02:04:06,000
So they went and met with him.

1205
02:04:06,000 --> 02:04:12,000
And that night, Dr. (Martin Luther) King called a mass rally in Cleveland, a big church there.

1206
02:04:12,000 --> 02:04:19,000
At Reverend Hoover's church, Odie M. Hoover.

1207
02:04:19,000 --> 02:04:24,000
And so Dr. (Martin Luther) King made this speech.

1208
02:04:24,000 --> 02:04:29,000
And in his speech, he talked about Sealtest.

1209
02:04:29,000 --> 02:04:31,000
And he talked about me.

1210
02:04:31,000 --> 02:04:36,000
He said, you know, we've made a major breakthrough here.

1211
02:04:36,000 --> 02:04:38,000
Like we haven't made in a while.

1212
02:04:38,000 --> 02:04:42,000
He said, but what Sealtest didn't realize it.

1213
02:04:42,000 --> 02:04:45,000
We had Bob Brown on our side.

1214
02:04:45,000 --> 02:04:47,000
And he's on our board directors.

1215
02:04:47,000 --> 02:04:51,000
And he was a man who made this stuff happen and so forth.

1216
02:04:51,000 --> 02:04:53,000
And it's recorded.

1217
02:04:53,000 --> 02:04:55,000
There's a recording about this.

1218
02:04:55,000 --> 02:04:58,000
You know, I have one somewhere in the office or somewhere.

1219
02:04:58,000 --> 02:05:02,000
There's a recording on his speech and what he was talking about.

1220
02:05:02,000 --> 02:05:05,000
He said, this is what we're going to do now.

1221
02:05:05,000 --> 02:05:08,000
There's a way of the future.

1222
02:05:08,000 --> 02:05:16,000
And he talked about my role in everything else and what I'd done for SEAL.

1223
02:05:16,000 --> 02:05:20,000
So it was an amazing time.

1224
02:05:20,000 --> 02:05:22,000
It's an amazing time.

1225
02:05:22,000 --> 02:05:28,000
I mean, as I said, when we started, there's a couple of hours ago that it's not just the, you know, the marches.

1226
02:05:28,000 --> 02:05:33,000
But it's these kinds of pressures and arm twisting in the back.

1227
02:05:33,000 --> 02:05:35,000
This is how this changes.

1228
02:05:35,000 --> 02:05:42,000
If you're not doing that, if you're not making something happen, because it's all about jobs and different kinds of opportunities.

1229
02:05:42,000 --> 02:05:46,000
Contracts with minority business people, all of this.

1230
02:05:46,000 --> 02:05:49,000
This is what makes the whole thing go around.

1231
02:05:49,000 --> 02:05:51,000
This is what makes it all a success.

1232
02:05:51,000 --> 02:05:55,000
You know, because the businesses and the jobs are going on all the time.

1233
02:05:55,000 --> 02:05:59,000
It's just that you need participation by all the people.

1234
02:05:59,000 --> 02:06:03,000
Blacks, Browns, Graves, whatever they are.

1235
02:06:03,000 --> 02:06:05,000
You need all the people to participate.

1236
02:06:05,000 --> 02:06:17,000
And during the 50s and the 60s for the most part, and sometimes in the 70s, you had only the whites who were participating in all this.

1237
02:06:17,000 --> 02:06:23,000
They had SEAL tests and the rest of the milk companies didn't even have any black.

1238
02:06:23,000 --> 02:06:27,000
They were taken milk throughout all these communities.

1239
02:06:27,000 --> 02:06:31,000
They had thousands of trucks and truck drivers delivered milk.

1240
02:06:31,000 --> 02:06:33,000
You remember the milk truck driver?

1241
02:06:33,000 --> 02:06:35,000
They didn't have any blacks.

1242
02:06:35,000 --> 02:06:36,000
Not a single driver.

1243
02:06:36,000 --> 02:06:37,000
Not a single driver.

1244
02:06:37,000 --> 02:06:40,000
They're living black people milk every which way.

1245
02:06:40,000 --> 02:06:42,000
Thousands of black people.

1246
02:06:42,000 --> 02:06:43,000
Ten thousand.

1247
02:06:43,000 --> 02:06:44,000
Didn't have one single driver.

1248
02:06:44,000 --> 02:06:46,000
Black.

1249
02:06:46,000 --> 02:06:49,000
We changed that.

1250
02:06:49,000 --> 02:06:55,000
You know, there are just so many different things like that that happened doing that to it.

1251
02:06:55,000 --> 02:06:59,000
I mean, a lot of people look at stuff now and they think it just happened.

1252
02:06:59,000 --> 02:07:04,000
You know, like out of the clear booth guy, somebody just got religion one day and said,

1253
02:07:04,000 --> 02:07:06,000
we're going to help black people.

1254
02:07:06,000 --> 02:07:08,000
You know, no, I didn't have like that.

1255
02:07:08,000 --> 02:07:10,000
You had to do some pressure put on them.

1256
02:07:10,000 --> 02:07:13,000
And that's what has to happen now.

1257
02:07:13,000 --> 02:07:23,000
I mean, you know, this thing with Mr. Obama taking the money away from the black causes

1258
02:07:23,000 --> 02:07:31,000
and there are tens of thousands of students who can't go back to school right now, black kids,

1259
02:07:31,000 --> 02:07:39,000
because they tighten up the money, the credit qurets, on the parents who could not get the loans anymore,

1260
02:07:39,000 --> 02:07:44,000
because the administration did that, you know.

1261
02:07:44,000 --> 02:07:49,000
And so many of the black colleges you watch over the next year or two,

1262
02:07:49,000 --> 02:07:52,000
many of the black colleges are going to be closing now.

1263
02:07:52,000 --> 02:07:55,000
You can't stay up and they don't have students.

1264
02:07:55,000 --> 02:07:59,000
So you tell me when.

1265
02:07:59,000 --> 02:08:04,000
Okay, so I'll just ask you, if you have any concluding remarks you'd like to make.

1266
02:08:04,000 --> 02:08:12,000
I mean, anything that I didn't ask you that I should have asked or you were expecting me to ask that I didn't or anything else you'd like to ask.

1267
02:08:12,000 --> 02:08:16,000
No, I think you've done a great job.

1268
02:08:16,000 --> 02:08:23,000
I appreciate you coming and appreciate what you all are doing.

1269
02:08:23,000 --> 02:08:32,000
Not just for your departments and history departments, all that, but for what to me, Zim is doing.

1270
02:08:32,000 --> 02:08:41,000
And what it will represent to ages yet unborn to those kids and to many of the young people today,

1271
02:08:41,000 --> 02:08:46,000
they have absolutely no idea what we're going on.

1272
02:08:46,000 --> 02:08:51,000
And they'll get this from this museum and what you all are doing now.

1273
02:08:51,000 --> 02:08:58,000
And it'll be a guidepost for many people, white, black, whoever,

1274
02:08:58,000 --> 02:09:06,000
to see what has happened and to give them some sense of what they ought to be doing in the years ahead.

1275
02:09:06,000 --> 02:09:10,000
So I appreciate what you've done and what you continue to do.

1276
02:09:10,000 --> 02:09:12,000
Well, thank you so much.

1277
02:09:12,000 --> 02:09:17,000
And yeah, it's been a battle just to get the museum as you know.

1278
02:09:17,000 --> 02:09:26,000
But I never thought that we would have a black history museum right there in the heart of Washington

1279
02:09:26,000 --> 02:09:33,000
in the probably the most proud spot that you can put a museum in the capital of the world.

1280
02:09:33,000 --> 02:09:35,000
I think it's fantastic.

1281
02:09:35,000 --> 02:09:42,000
Every time I go by the, I just tear just well up in my eyes now, you know, and I'm back at fourth and watched an all day.

1282
02:09:42,000 --> 02:09:46,000
But I just, I think it's a wonderful, magnificent thing.

1283
02:09:46,000 --> 02:09:54,000
And I congratulate you, all of you, for what you've done, and especially Lonnie and the board and everybody involved.

1284
02:09:54,000 --> 02:09:56,000
I think we've done a great job.

1285
02:09:56,000 --> 02:10:06,000
And I'm looking forward to seeing the finished product and to getting a lot of young people, blacks and whites and others there.

1286
02:10:06,000 --> 02:10:12,000
And particularly all of the young people from Africa, I think they need to see this.

1287
02:10:12,000 --> 02:10:15,000
That would help them a great deal.

1288
02:10:15,000 --> 02:10:17,000
And I'm in touch with a lot of them.

1289
02:10:17,000 --> 02:10:21,000
We're still sending a lot of books in the schools there.

1290
02:10:21,000 --> 02:10:25,000
And many of them who can come over here to visit.

1291
02:10:25,000 --> 02:10:27,000
So I'm going to be taking them.

1292
02:10:27,000 --> 02:10:30,000
You finished. I will be taking a lot of them to that museum.

1293
02:10:30,000 --> 02:10:31,000
Fantastic.

1294
02:10:31,000 --> 02:10:33,000
Well, what a great way to end.

1295
02:10:33,000 --> 02:10:34,000
Well, thank you so much.

1296
02:10:34,000 --> 02:10:35,000
Thank you.

1297
02:10:35,000 --> 02:10:38,000
It's been just a little bit.

1298
02:10:38,000 --> 02:10:47,000
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.
